WEBVTT

1
00:02:53.630 --> 00:02:54.880
(SOBBING)

2
00:03:00.720 --> 00:03:02.140
SON: Dad.

3
00:03:32.380 --> 00:03:34.010
<i>(WAVES CRASHING)</i>

4
00:04:14.420 --> 00:04:16.010
(MOTOR HUMMING)

5
00:04:41.160 --> 00:04:42.530
(RETCHING)

6
00:04:47.830 --> 00:04:52.080
Clear the ramp! 30 seconds!
God be with you!

7
00:04:52.170 --> 00:04:57.420
Port side stick, starboard side stick,
move fast and clear those murder holes.

8
00:04:57.510 --> 00:04:59.840
I want to see plenty of beach
between men.

9
00:04:59.930 --> 00:05:03.850
Five men is a juicy opportunity.
One man is a waste of ammo.

10
00:05:03.930 --> 00:05:06.020
Keep the sand out of your weapons.

11
00:05:06.140 --> 00:05:10.520
Keep those actions clear.
And I'll see you on the beach.

12
00:05:10.850 --> 00:05:12.310
(EXPLOSIONS)

13
00:05:42.680 --> 00:05:44.890
CAPTAIN: Clear the murder holes!

14
00:05:45.800 --> 00:05:47.640
(BULLETS BUZZING)

15
00:06:01.240 --> 00:06:02.780
Over the side!

16
00:06:09.290 --> 00:06:11.710
CAPTAIN: Port and starboard, over...

17
00:06:48.530 --> 00:06:50.450
(CONTINUOUS EXPLOSIONS)

18
00:07:07.970 --> 00:07:09.640
(FAINT SCREAMING)

19
00:07:16.100 --> 00:07:17.400
(GASPING)

20
00:07:20.900 --> 00:07:22.150
Jesus.

21
00:07:22.610 --> 00:07:24.360
Thank you...

22
00:07:31.330 --> 00:07:33.290
(BULLETS HITTING METAL)

23
00:08:36.100 --> 00:08:37.730
(SOUND DISTORTS)

24
00:08:57.330 --> 00:08:58.750
(EXPLOSION)

25
00:09:38.580 --> 00:09:40.040
(MOUTHING)

26
00:09:43.250 --> 00:09:46.300
I said, what the hell do we do now, sir?

27
00:09:47.760 --> 00:09:50.970
HORVATH: Captain Miller!
Captain Miller!

28
00:09:52.630 --> 00:09:55.800
- Captain Miller!
- Sergeant Horvath!

29
00:09:57.350 --> 00:10:01.020
Move your men off the beach! Go!

30
00:10:01.140 --> 00:10:02.440
Okay, you guys!

31
00:10:02.520 --> 00:10:05.610
- Get on my ass! Follow me!
- Sir!

32
00:10:05.980 --> 00:10:07.980
What's the rallying point?

33
00:10:08.110 --> 00:10:09.900
Anywhere but here!

34
00:10:11.320 --> 00:10:13.280
(CONTINUOUS EXPLOSIONS)

35
00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:25.460
The seawall! Move up to the seawall!

36
00:10:25.540 --> 00:10:27.840
SOLDIER: Sir, I'm staying!

37
00:10:27.920 --> 00:10:30.210
Clear this beach!
Make way for the others!

38
00:10:30.340 --> 00:10:32.880
This is all we got
between us and the Almighty.

39
00:10:33.010 --> 00:10:37.010
Every inch of this beach
has been pre-sighted!

40
00:10:37.890 --> 00:10:41.180
You stay here, you're dead men!

41
00:10:41.430 --> 00:10:43.100
(MACHINE GUN FIRING)

42
00:10:54.400 --> 00:10:57.950
Mama! Mama!

43
00:10:58.950 --> 00:11:00.370
(SCREAMING)

44
00:11:02.580 --> 00:11:05.080
Stay down! Stay down!

45
00:11:09.750 --> 00:11:11.090
What are you guys?

46
00:11:11.170 --> 00:11:13.880
104th Medical Battalion, sir!

47
00:11:13.970 --> 00:11:16.640
Here to set up field operations!

48
00:11:16.720 --> 00:11:18.260
Get rid of that crap!

49
00:11:18.350 --> 00:11:21.430
Grab yourselves some weapons.
Follow me.

50
00:11:25.310 --> 00:11:27.060
(SCREAMING IN PAIN)

51
00:11:29.020 --> 00:11:31.940
- BRIGGS: I'm hit! I'm hit!
- Briggs!

52
00:11:36.200 --> 00:11:40.490
Get me out of here. I'm hit low. God!

53
00:11:40.580 --> 00:11:43.660
- Medic!
- Navy Beach Battalion, sir.

54
00:11:43.750 --> 00:11:47.460
I gotta clear these obstacles,
make holes for the tanks.

55
00:11:47.540 --> 00:11:49.880
All the armor is foundering
in the Channel.

56
00:11:49.960 --> 00:11:53.210
Orders, sir. You go somewhere else.
I'm clearing this one!

57
00:11:53.300 --> 00:11:54.800
Come on, Briggs!

58
00:11:54.880 --> 00:11:56.720
(BULLETS BUZZING)

59
00:11:59.680 --> 00:12:01.050
MILLER: Medic!

60
00:12:05.770 --> 00:12:07.390
(SOUND DISTORTS)

61
00:12:38.130 --> 00:12:39.760
MILLER: Move! Move!

62
00:12:47.430 --> 00:12:50.560
Move! Come on! Move!

63
00:13:12.330 --> 00:13:15.670
Shore party.
No armor has made it ashore.

64
00:13:15.750 --> 00:13:20.470
We got no DD tanks on the beach.
Dog One is not open.

65
00:13:21.430 --> 00:13:25.060
- Who's in command here?
- You are, sir!

66
00:13:26.680 --> 00:13:29.140
- Sergeant Horvath!
- Sir!

67
00:13:29.230 --> 00:13:31.270
You recognize where we are?

68
00:13:31.350 --> 00:13:33.770
Right where we're supposed to be,
but no one else is!

69
00:13:33.860 --> 00:13:37.320
Nobody's where they're supposed to be.

70
00:13:37.400 --> 00:13:38.990
Shore party.

71
00:13:39.780 --> 00:13:42.030
First wave, ineffective.

72
00:13:42.110 --> 00:13:46.160
We do not hold the beach.
Say again, we do not hold the beach.

73
00:13:46.540 --> 00:13:47.910
We're all mixed up, sir.

74
00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:49.790
We got the leftovers from Fox Company,

75
00:13:49.870 --> 00:13:51.830
Able Company and George Company!

76
00:13:51.920 --> 00:13:55.540
Plus we got some Navy demo guys
and a beach-master!

77
00:13:57.090 --> 00:14:00.090
Shore party. Shore party.

78
00:14:06.180 --> 00:14:08.520
CATF, CATF...

79
00:14:12.020 --> 00:14:14.310
- Reiben here, sir!
- Did you see anybody else?

80
00:14:14.400 --> 00:14:17.190
- Jackson, but that's about it.
- Mellish here.

81
00:14:17.270 --> 00:14:20.530
Caparzo! We got DeForest
back there with Wade.

82
00:14:20.610 --> 00:14:24.360
He's hurt so bad he says
he sprung 100 leaks.

83
00:14:24.450 --> 00:14:26.120
Wade says he's all used up.

84
00:14:26.200 --> 00:14:28.450
- Move on to somebody you can help.
- Let's go!

85
00:14:28.540 --> 00:14:31.000
He's battalion surgeon, sir!

86
00:14:35.040 --> 00:14:37.000
- Get his attention.
- Wade!

87
00:14:37.090 --> 00:14:38.590
- Yo, Doc!
- Wade!

88
00:14:38.670 --> 00:14:41.840
- Wade! Wade! Wade!
- Wade!

89
00:14:42.880 --> 00:14:46.180
- Wade! Wade! Wade!
- Too risky, Doc. Too risky.

90
00:14:47.640 --> 00:14:49.720
- Wade!
- All right. Get him off the beach.

91
00:14:49.810 --> 00:14:53.560
I got it! We stopped the bleeding!
We stopped the bleeding!

92
00:14:55.100 --> 00:14:56.730
Fuck!

93
00:14:56.810 --> 00:15:00.110
Just give us a fucking chance,
you son of a bitch!

94
00:15:00.190 --> 00:15:02.610
- Son of a fucking cocksucker!
- MELLISH: Wade! Come on. Come on.

95
00:15:02.690 --> 00:15:05.910
Wade! It's Mellish! Wade!

96
00:15:06.450 --> 00:15:08.120
- Mellish!
- MELLISH: Let's go!

97
00:15:08.200 --> 00:15:09.370
We found Miller!

98
00:15:09.450 --> 00:15:11.660
- Fuck it!
- Let's move! Let's move!

99
00:15:11.750 --> 00:15:13.000
(CRYING)

100
00:15:19.090 --> 00:15:22.210
This is all? This is all that's made it?

101
00:15:22.300 --> 00:15:25.800
We got scattered pretty bad, sir.
There's bound to be more.

102
00:15:26.800 --> 00:15:29.140
- Not enough. It's not enough.
- Dog One exit...

103
00:15:29.220 --> 00:15:30.660
It's gotta be that cut on the right.

104
00:15:30.680 --> 00:15:33.180
- Or is that one on the left? Shit!
- No. No, no, no.

105
00:15:33.270 --> 00:15:35.980
Vierville is to the west of us.
This is Dog One.

106
00:15:36.060 --> 00:15:37.310
They're killing us!

107
00:15:37.400 --> 00:15:41.530
And we don't have a fucking chance,
and that ain't fair!

108
00:15:41.610 --> 00:15:43.990
Gather weapons and ammo!

109
00:15:44.070 --> 00:15:45.900
Gather weapons and ammo!

110
00:15:45.990 --> 00:15:49.070
Come on, let's drag them in
off the sand!

111
00:15:57.170 --> 00:16:01.090
Reiben. Hey, Reiben, Reiben, Reiben,
where's your BAR?

112
00:16:01.840 --> 00:16:04.040
Bottom of the channel, sir.
The bitch tried to drown me.

113
00:16:04.050 --> 00:16:05.920
Find a replacement.

114
00:16:07.970 --> 00:16:10.930
Bangalores! Bring up some bangalores!

115
00:16:12.350 --> 00:16:15.890
Grenades, grenades! Get me
some grenades. Get them over here!

116
00:16:18.560 --> 00:16:22.570
Bangalores up the line!
Bangalores up the line!

117
00:16:22.650 --> 00:16:24.940
Heads up! Bangers coming your way!

118
00:16:25.030 --> 00:16:27.450
Come on, come on, come on!

119
00:16:27.530 --> 00:16:30.370
- Jackson here, sir!
- Reiben back, sir!

120
00:16:31.030 --> 00:16:33.790
SOLDIER: on, my God!

121
00:16:36.790 --> 00:16:39.250
One more. Give me one more.

122
00:16:40.330 --> 00:16:42.130
(SOLDIER YELLING)

123
00:16:44.590 --> 00:16:47.300
Oh, my God, it hurts! I'm gonna die!

124
00:16:47.380 --> 00:16:51.340
Oh, my God! Oh, Jesus! Oh, my God!

125
00:16:52.470 --> 00:16:55.890
Keep it moving. Keep it moving.
Almost got it.

126
00:16:55.970 --> 00:16:59.020
- Jesus! Lucky bastard.
- Come on.

127
00:16:59.900 --> 00:17:02.190
- Move it!
- Keep it moving. You got it?

128
00:17:02.270 --> 00:17:05.320
SOLDIER: God! God, help me!

129
00:17:05.940 --> 00:17:07.860
You're not gonna die.
You're not gonna die.

130
00:17:07.940 --> 00:17:11.110
You're fine. Don't look at it.
Don't look at it.

131
00:17:11.200 --> 00:17:14.950
Bangalores! Clear the shingle!

132
00:17:15.040 --> 00:17:17.700
- Fire in the hole!
- Fire in the hole!

133
00:17:17.790 --> 00:17:20.330
Fire in the hole!

134
00:17:21.500 --> 00:17:23.250
Fire in the hole!

135
00:17:32.840 --> 00:17:36.560
We're in business! Defilade!
Other side of the hole!

136
00:17:49.610 --> 00:17:51.950
SENIOR MEDICI That's it! Let's go!

137
00:17:55.410 --> 00:17:57.540
Inspected. Morphine.

138
00:18:00.410 --> 00:18:01.790
Routine.

139
00:18:07.800 --> 00:18:09.260
Priority.

140
00:18:13.260 --> 00:18:14.470
He's gone.

141
00:18:17.640 --> 00:18:19.850
(MACHINE GUN FIRING
CONTINUOUSLY)

142
00:18:26.900 --> 00:18:28.650
Son of a...

143
00:18:29.400 --> 00:18:32.070
- Get in there.
- Fuck. I can't move.

144
00:18:32.150 --> 00:18:33.410
- Mellish.
- Yes, sir.

145
00:18:33.490 --> 00:18:35.320
Give me your bayonet.

146
00:18:47.880 --> 00:18:49.250
(EXPLOSION)

147
00:18:55.510 --> 00:18:59.260
Two MG42s and two mortars.
Add 20, left 30.

148
00:19:02.350 --> 00:19:05.100
There's a little defilade over there,
but it's the perfect fire position

149
00:19:05.190 --> 00:19:06.940
if we get some goddamn armor
on the beach.

150
00:19:07.020 --> 00:19:10.110
We gotta open up this draw!
We gotta get this draw open.

151
00:19:10.190 --> 00:19:12.110
Reiben, Mellish, let's get into the war!

152
00:19:12.190 --> 00:19:15.200
Grab some cover
and put some fire on that crew.

153
00:19:15.280 --> 00:19:18.990
Davis, Debernardo,
Young, Valk, get ready.

154
00:19:21.330 --> 00:19:23.040
Covering fire!

155
00:19:26.370 --> 00:19:28.080
MILLER: Go, go, go!

156
00:19:42.100 --> 00:19:44.060
Goddamn firing squad.

157
00:19:44.180 --> 00:19:47.350
It's the only way we can get
everybody the hell out of here.

158
00:19:47.440 --> 00:19:51.650
Short, Payton, McDonald, Parkes!
You're next!

159
00:19:51.730 --> 00:19:54.360
Why don't we just hand out
blindfolds, Cap?

160
00:19:54.440 --> 00:19:56.030
All we can do here is die.

161
00:19:56.110 --> 00:19:57.700
Covering fire!

162
00:20:00.200 --> 00:20:01.950
Go, go, go!

163
00:20:03.200 --> 00:20:04.910
Come on! Come on! Come on!

164
00:20:05.040 --> 00:20:06.920
Go, God damn it!

165
00:20:19.260 --> 00:20:21.930
- Jackson.
- Sir.

166
00:20:23.140 --> 00:20:24.720
- Do you see that impact crater?
- Yes, sir.

167
00:20:24.810 --> 00:20:27.190
That should give you complete defilade
from that machine-gun position.

168
00:20:27.270 --> 00:20:29.150
Get in there and give me
some fire discipline.

169
00:20:29.270 --> 00:20:31.150
Wait for my command.

170
00:20:36.900 --> 00:20:38.280
Go!

171
00:20:49.330 --> 00:20:52.630
Captain, if your mother saw you do that,
she'd be very upset.

172
00:20:52.750 --> 00:20:55.000
I thought you were my mother.

173
00:20:55.840 --> 00:20:58.590
Be not thou far from me, O Lord.

174
00:21:03.140 --> 00:21:07.140
O my God, I am heartily sorry
for having offended thee.

175
00:21:08.350 --> 00:21:10.600
I detest my sins
for having offended thee, O Lord.

176
00:21:10.690 --> 00:21:12.230
I detest my sins for having
offended thee, O Lord.

177
00:21:12.310 --> 00:21:13.650
Listen to me, Lord.

178
00:21:13.770 --> 00:21:15.480
(PRAYING IN LATIN)

179
00:21:19.610 --> 00:21:23.200
All my strength, haste thee to help me.

180
00:21:39.010 --> 00:21:44.010
- Dog One exit! Right here!
- We're in business!

181
00:21:45.560 --> 00:21:47.270
Move! Move!

182
00:22:28.720 --> 00:22:30.350
- Reiben.
- MILLER: Let's go, Sarge. Go!

183
00:22:30.430 --> 00:22:31.730
Reiben.

184
00:22:56.580 --> 00:22:59.050
SOLDIER: The place is full of 'em!

185
00:23:00.590 --> 00:23:02.260
MILLER: Come on, Doyle!

186
00:23:03.760 --> 00:23:05.180
Sarge?

187
00:23:10.520 --> 00:23:13.600
- Flame!
- Doyle, do it!

188
00:23:18.110 --> 00:23:20.780
Don't shoot! Let them burn!

189
00:23:37.710 --> 00:23:39.710
(SURRENDERING IN GERMAN)

190
00:23:42.760 --> 00:23:46.050
SOLDIER 1: I'll give you "comrade,"
you son of a bitch!

191
00:23:46.130 --> 00:23:47.800
SOLDIER 2: Lie down!

192
00:24:16.000 --> 00:24:18.500
Cease fire! Cease fire!

193
00:24:18.580 --> 00:24:21.750
Cut it out! Cut it out! Cease fire!

194
00:24:22.840 --> 00:24:24.510
Sugar Cane. Sugar Charlie 3.

195
00:24:24.630 --> 00:24:27.840
Say again, Dog One is open.
Send in the dozers.

196
00:24:27.970 --> 00:24:29.840
I'm waiting for you
to tie in my flanks. Over.

197
00:24:29.930 --> 00:24:31.720
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

198
00:24:32.010 --> 00:24:33.470
What?

199
00:24:33.560 --> 00:24:35.600
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

200
00:24:36.100 --> 00:24:39.440
What? I'm sorry, I can't understand
what you're saying.

201
00:24:47.360 --> 00:24:49.950
What did he say? What did he say?

202
00:24:50.030 --> 00:24:53.200
"Look, I washed for supper."

203
00:24:57.830 --> 00:24:59.330
God damn it!

204
00:25:05.710 --> 00:25:07.300
- Hey, Fish.
- Yeah?

205
00:25:07.380 --> 00:25:10.050
Look at this. A Hitler Youth knife.

206
00:25:11.550 --> 00:25:14.720
And now
it's a Shabbat challah cutter, right?

207
00:25:18.310 --> 00:25:19.600
(MOANING)

208
00:25:24.650 --> 00:25:26.320
MILLER: Keep it moving!

209
00:25:34.910 --> 00:25:36.240
(SOBBING)

210
00:26:26.500 --> 00:26:28.380
HORVATH: That's quite a view.

211
00:26:29.340 --> 00:26:30.880
Yes, it is.

212
00:26:32.590 --> 00:26:34.140
Quite a view.

213
00:26:42.060 --> 00:26:44.230
(WAVES CRASHING)

214
00:27:57.590 --> 00:27:59.390
(TYPEWRITER CLACKING)

215
00:28:08.940 --> 00:28:11.110
<i>MAN 1: "Dear Mr. Brian Boyd,"</i>

216
00:28:11.190 --> 00:28:13.360
<i>"no doubt by now you have
received full information..."</i>

217
00:28:13.440 --> 00:28:15.650
<i>MAN 2: "Dear Mrs. Jensen..."
MAN 1: "...untimely death of your son."</i>

218
00:28:15.740 --> 00:28:17.660
<i>MAN 2: "...no words of mine
can ever relieve the grief..."</i>

219
00:28:17.740 --> 00:28:20.030
<i>MAN 3: "Our outfit
has felt his loss tremendously."</i>

220
00:28:20.120 --> 00:28:22.870
<i>MAN 4: "He was a fine soldier
and he believed very strongly in..."</i>

221
00:28:22.950 --> 00:28:25.660
<i>MAN 5: "It's no secret anymore
that we were involved</i>

222
00:28:25.750 --> 00:28:27.870
<i>"in one of the most important
operations of this war."</i>

223
00:28:27.920 --> 00:28:30.460
<i>MAN 1: "Al was the one
who held us all together."</i>

224
00:28:30.540 --> 00:28:31.790
<i>"He was always the
first to volunteer..."</i>

225
00:28:31.880 --> 00:28:33.520
<i>MAN 6: "...came to a clearing
near a road"</i>

226
00:28:33.550 --> 00:28:35.510
<i>"where over 4,000 troops had passed..."</i>

227
00:28:35.590 --> 00:28:37.800
<i>MAN 7: "Your husband
served in a combat unit"</i>

228
00:28:37.880 --> 00:28:40.430
<i>"whose dangerous duty
is to place itself..."</i>

229
00:28:40.510 --> 00:28:43.640
<i>MAN 8: "...which we all cherish
and hold so dear."</i>

230
00:28:43.720 --> 00:28:47.440
<i>"The loss of Lee and others like him
is a distinct blow to the regiment."</i>

231
00:28:47.520 --> 00:28:48.810
<i>MAN 9: "I fully understand your desire"</i>

232
00:28:48.900 --> 00:28:51.560
<i>"to learn as much as possible
regarding the circumstances"</i>

233
00:28:51.650 --> 00:28:53.770
<i>"leading to his death."</i>

234
00:29:45.950 --> 00:29:47.700
Colonel, I've got something
you should know about.

235
00:29:47.790 --> 00:29:49.080
Yes.

236
00:29:51.080 --> 00:29:53.630
These two men died in Normandy.

237
00:29:54.250 --> 00:29:57.090
This one at Omaha Beach.

238
00:29:57.170 --> 00:30:00.630
- Sean Ryan.
- This man at Utah.

239
00:30:02.300 --> 00:30:04.010
Peter Ryan.

240
00:30:07.770 --> 00:30:10.850
This man was killed
last week in New Guinea.

241
00:30:13.600 --> 00:30:16.020
Daniel Ryan.

242
00:30:16.730 --> 00:30:18.650
The three men are brothers, sir.

243
00:30:18.730 --> 00:30:20.190
I've just learned that, this afternoon,

244
00:30:20.280 --> 00:30:24.070
their mother is going
to be getting all three telegrams.

245
00:30:27.030 --> 00:30:29.290
That's not all. There's a
fourth brother. The youngest.

246
00:30:29.370 --> 00:30:31.370
He parachuted in
with the 101st Airborne,

247
00:30:31.460 --> 00:30:32.920
night before the invasion.

248
00:30:33.000 --> 00:30:34.880
He's somewhere in Normandy.
We don't know where.

249
00:30:34.920 --> 00:30:37.340
- Is he alive?
- We don't know.

250
00:30:41.510 --> 00:30:43.130
Come with me.

251
00:32:26.950 --> 00:32:29.320
<i>MARSHALL: God damn it.</i>

252
00:32:30.160 --> 00:32:31.990
All four of them
were in the same company

253
00:32:32.080 --> 00:32:34.080
in the 29th Division,
but we split them up

254
00:32:34.160 --> 00:32:36.000
after the Sullivan brothers died
on the Juneau.

255
00:32:36.750 --> 00:32:39.750
Any contact with the fourth son, James?

256
00:32:39.880 --> 00:32:43.840
No, sir. He was dropped about
15 miles inland near Neuville.

257
00:32:43.920 --> 00:32:45.210
But that's still deep
behind German lines.

258
00:32:45.300 --> 00:32:47.510
Now, Mac,
there is no way you can know

259
00:32:47.590 --> 00:32:50.510
where in the hell he was dropped.

260
00:32:50.590 --> 00:32:52.590
General, first reports out of
Ike's people at SHAEF

261
00:32:52.640 --> 00:32:54.560
said the 101st is scattered
all to hell and gone.

262
00:32:54.600 --> 00:32:56.980
There's mis-drops all over Normandy.

263
00:32:57.060 --> 00:32:59.980
Now, assuming Private Ryan
even survived the jump,

264
00:33:00.060 --> 00:33:01.520
he could be anywhere.

265
00:33:01.610 --> 00:33:03.650
In fact, he's probably KIA.

266
00:33:03.730 --> 00:33:07.400
And frankly, sir, we go sending
some sort of rescue mission,

267
00:33:07.490 --> 00:33:10.070
flat-hatting throughout swarms
of German reinforcements

268
00:33:10.160 --> 00:33:13.990
all along our axis of advance,
they're gonna be KIA, too.

269
00:33:36.520 --> 00:33:38.560
I have a letter here,

270
00:33:39.940 --> 00:33:44.020
written a long time ago
to a Mrs. Bixby in Boston.

271
00:33:44.110 --> 00:33:46.030
So bear with me.

272
00:33:48.860 --> 00:33:50.400
"Dear Madam,"

273
00:33:51.110 --> 00:33:53.370
"I have been shown in the files
of the War Department"

274
00:33:53.450 --> 00:33:57.200
"a statement of the Adjutant
General of Massachusetts"

275
00:33:57.290 --> 00:34:00.620
"that you are the mother of five"

276
00:34:03.630 --> 00:34:07.340
"sons who have died gloriously
on the field of battle."

277
00:34:10.010 --> 00:34:13.760
"I feel how weak and fruitless
must be any words of mine"

278
00:34:14.550 --> 00:34:17.930
"that would attempt
to beguile you from the grief"

279
00:34:18.350 --> 00:34:20.770
"of a loss so overwhelming."

280
00:34:22.600 --> 00:34:24.610
"But I cannot refrain
from tendering to you"

281
00:34:24.690 --> 00:34:27.860
"the consolation that may be found"

282
00:34:27.940 --> 00:34:32.200
"in the thanks of the republic
they died to save."

283
00:34:36.370 --> 00:34:37.690
"I pray that Our Heavenly Father"

284
00:34:37.740 --> 00:34:40.830
"may assuage the anguish
of your bereavement"

285
00:34:40.910 --> 00:34:45.290
"and leave you only the cherished
memory of the loved lost,"

286
00:34:46.420 --> 00:34:48.050
"and the solemn pride
that must be yours"

287
00:34:48.130 --> 00:34:52.420
"to have laid so costly a sacrifice
upon the altar of freedom."

288
00:34:53.010 --> 00:34:56.180
"Yours very sincerely and respectfully,"

289
00:34:56.260 --> 00:34:58.100
"Abraham Lincoln."

290
00:35:16.950 --> 00:35:18.780
That boy is alive.

291
00:35:19.490 --> 00:35:22.410
We are gonna send somebody
to find him,

292
00:35:23.540 --> 00:35:26.710
and we are gonna get him
the hell out of there.

293
00:35:27.750 --> 00:35:29.420
OFFICER 1: Yes, sir.
OFFICER 2: Yes, sir.

294
00:35:42.100 --> 00:35:44.560
We expected 32 tanks to float to
the beach. Twenty-seven didn't make it.

295
00:35:44.640 --> 00:35:46.690
- Miller, Charlie Company.
- Go on in, Captain.

296
00:35:46.770 --> 00:35:47.900
I understand your situation.

297
00:35:47.980 --> 00:35:51.070
But if we don't offload
those duel-drive Shermans by 0600,

298
00:35:51.150 --> 00:35:52.360
we're gonna have an entire division

299
00:35:52.440 --> 00:35:56.160
stuck at Carentan
with its pants around its ankles.

300
00:35:56.240 --> 00:35:58.660
Well, you let me know then.

301
00:35:58.740 --> 00:36:01.620
Have Charlie Company hold at Vierville
until we can get some armor up there.

302
00:36:01.700 --> 00:36:03.540
SOLDIER: Yes, sir. Runner!

303
00:36:10.000 --> 00:36:12.760
Airborne was supposed to win
an open door for the rest of us.

304
00:36:12.840 --> 00:36:15.480
Instead they mis-dropped, scattered
all their sticks into the wind.

305
00:36:15.510 --> 00:36:19.680
- What's your situation?
- Yes, sir. Sector four is secure.

306
00:36:20.050 --> 00:36:21.310
We...

307
00:36:21.890 --> 00:36:26.980
We took out towed 88s
here, here and here.

308
00:36:27.060 --> 00:36:28.730
They'd already gotten four
of our Shermans

309
00:36:28.810 --> 00:36:30.110
and a number
of our deuce and a halves.

310
00:36:30.190 --> 00:36:33.150
These two minefields
are actually one big one.

311
00:36:33.230 --> 00:36:34.900
We tried to make our way up
through the middle of it,

312
00:36:34.990 --> 00:36:37.360
but it turned into a mixed,
high-density field,

313
00:36:37.450 --> 00:36:38.570
little bit of everything.

314
00:36:38.660 --> 00:36:42.490
Spreng Mine 44s. Schu Mine 42s,
pot mines. A-200s,

315
00:36:42.580 --> 00:36:46.080
the little wooden bastards
that the mine detectors don't pick up.

316
00:36:46.160 --> 00:36:50.630
This road here, they placed
big mushrooms, Teller Mine 43s,

317
00:36:50.710 --> 00:36:51.880
I guess for our tanks,

318
00:36:51.960 --> 00:36:55.460
from here right up
to the edge of the village. Right here.

319
00:36:55.550 --> 00:36:57.510
So we marked them,
called the engineers.

320
00:36:57.590 --> 00:36:58.880
Resistance?

321
00:36:58.970 --> 00:37:01.180
We had higher
support expectations, sir.

322
00:37:01.260 --> 00:37:03.560
There was an under-strength
company without artillery.

323
00:37:03.640 --> 00:37:06.890
Wehrmacht 346 Infantry,
Von Luck Kampfgruppe.

324
00:37:06.980 --> 00:37:09.020
We ended up with 23 prisoners.

325
00:37:09.100 --> 00:37:12.270
We turned them over
to MPs from the 29th.

326
00:37:15.030 --> 00:37:17.320
What about our casualties?

327
00:37:17.950 --> 00:37:20.070
Well, the figures

328
00:37:21.450 --> 00:37:24.950
were 35 dead, times two wounded.

329
00:37:25.040 --> 00:37:28.290
They just didn't wanna
give up those 88s.

330
00:37:30.210 --> 00:37:32.960
It was a tough assignment.
That's why you got it.

331
00:37:33.040 --> 00:37:34.550
Yes, sir.

332
00:37:35.800 --> 00:37:37.300
John...

333
00:37:40.260 --> 00:37:42.180
I've got another one for you.

334
00:37:42.260 --> 00:37:45.220
- Yes, sir.
- This one's straight from the top.

335
00:37:51.810 --> 00:37:53.980
MILLER: You and I are taking a squad
over to Neuville

336
00:37:54.060 --> 00:37:55.980
on a public-relations mission.

337
00:37:56.070 --> 00:37:57.900
HORVATH: You leading a squad?

338
00:37:57.990 --> 00:38:01.110
MILLER: Some private in the 101st
lost three brothers,

339
00:38:01.200 --> 00:38:02.870
and he's got a ticket home.

340
00:38:02.950 --> 00:38:04.070
HORVATH: How come Neuville?

341
00:38:04.160 --> 00:38:05.370
MILLER: They think
he's up there somewhere,

342
00:38:05.450 --> 00:38:08.080
part of all those airborne mis-drops.

343
00:38:08.160 --> 00:38:10.870
HORVATH: It's not gonna be easy
finding one particular soldier

344
00:38:10.960 --> 00:38:12.120
in the middle of this
whole goddamn war.

345
00:38:12.210 --> 00:38:14.670
Like finding a needle
in a stack of needles.

346
00:38:14.750 --> 00:38:16.340
But what about the company?

347
00:38:16.420 --> 00:38:19.720
We take the pick of the litter
and the rest get folded into Baker.

348
00:38:19.800 --> 00:38:21.510
Jesus Christ.

349
00:38:21.590 --> 00:38:23.640
They took away your company?

350
00:38:23.720 --> 00:38:28.220
It wasn't my company. It was
the Army's. So they told me, anyway.

351
00:38:28.350 --> 00:38:32.270
Give me Reiben on BAR, Jackson,
Wade, Beasley and Caparzo.

352
00:38:32.350 --> 00:38:33.770
Beasley's dead.

353
00:38:33.850 --> 00:38:36.650
All right, Mellish, then.
We got anybody speaks French?

354
00:38:36.730 --> 00:38:40.570
- Not that I know of.
- What about Talbot?

355
00:38:40.690 --> 00:38:43.700
- This morning.
- Oh. All right.

356
00:38:44.110 --> 00:38:46.200
I'm gonna go try to dig up
another interpreter.

357
00:38:46.280 --> 00:38:48.080
Assemble at battalion motor pool
on the beach.

358
00:38:48.120 --> 00:38:49.200
Yes, sir.

359
00:38:49.290 --> 00:38:50.660
- Sarge, what we gonna do?
- Okay, listen up...

360
00:38:50.750 --> 00:38:52.120
- What?
- What are we gonna do?

361
00:38:52.210 --> 00:38:53.970
You're going home wrapped
in an American flag

362
00:38:54.040 --> 00:38:56.040
with a hunk of cheese
in your ass, Caparzo, you smart ass.

363
00:38:56.130 --> 00:38:57.880
- Now, listen up.
- I thought you liked it in the ass.

364
00:38:57.960 --> 00:38:59.680
- What?
- I thought you liked it in the ass.

365
00:38:59.960 --> 00:39:02.090
Attention!

366
00:39:02.220 --> 00:39:03.430
As you were.

367
00:39:03.550 --> 00:39:05.590
I'm looking
for Corporal Upham, Timothy E.

368
00:39:05.720 --> 00:39:07.010
Yes, sir. I'm Upham, sir.

369
00:39:07.100 --> 00:39:08.720
I understand you speak
French and German.

370
00:39:08.810 --> 00:39:10.600
- Yes, sir.
- How's your accent?

371
00:39:10.720 --> 00:39:12.350
Just a slight one in French,
but my German's clean.

372
00:39:12.430 --> 00:39:14.150
- Has a touch of Bavarian, sir.
- Very good.

373
00:39:14.230 --> 00:39:15.770
You've been reassigned to me.
Grab your gear.

374
00:39:15.900 --> 00:39:18.230
- We're going to a place called Neuville.
- Yes, sir.

375
00:39:18.320 --> 00:39:20.480
- When was this updated?
- Updated as of 0830 hour this morning.

376
00:39:20.570 --> 00:39:22.820
- Sir...
- This is the 12th SS Panzer.

377
00:39:22.900 --> 00:39:24.740
These are the two axes
that advance south.

378
00:39:24.820 --> 00:39:27.280
- Sir, there are Germans in Neuville.
- There are artillery up here, sir.

379
00:39:27.410 --> 00:39:30.080
- That's what I understand. Corporal.
- Yes, sir.

380
00:39:30.160 --> 00:39:32.330
Sir, there are a lot
of Germans in Neuville.

381
00:39:32.410 --> 00:39:33.500
You have a problem with that, Corporal?

382
00:39:33.580 --> 00:39:36.040
No, sir. Just if you consider
I've never been in combat, sir.

383
00:39:36.120 --> 00:39:37.760
I make maps and I translate.
And that's...

384
00:39:37.830 --> 00:39:40.750
I need someone who speaks
French and German.

385
00:39:40.840 --> 00:39:42.590
- Yes, sir.
- My two guys were killed.

386
00:39:42.670 --> 00:39:45.340
Yes, sir. It's just that I haven't
held a weapon since basic training, sir.

387
00:39:45.430 --> 00:39:48.050
Did you fire the weapon
in basic training?

388
00:39:48.140 --> 00:39:49.350
Yes, sir.

389
00:39:49.430 --> 00:39:52.180
- Well, then, get your gear.
- Yes, sir.

390
00:39:53.310 --> 00:39:55.600
Sir, may I bring...

391
00:39:59.360 --> 00:40:01.860
May I bring my typewriter, sir?

392
00:40:06.950 --> 00:40:08.280
Yes, sir.

393
00:40:11.540 --> 00:40:13.330
Thank you very much, sir.

394
00:40:13.450 --> 00:40:15.790
- That a souvenir?
- No, sir.

395
00:40:15.870 --> 00:40:18.040
Take your time, Corporal.

396
00:40:22.380 --> 00:40:24.920
You should look
on the bright side of things, Corporal.

397
00:40:25.010 --> 00:40:26.130
Yes, sir.

398
00:40:26.220 --> 00:40:29.260
For one thing,
you don't need to carry those.

399
00:40:29.340 --> 00:40:32.310
- You'll need that.
- I'll need that, sir. Yes, sir.

400
00:41:17.850 --> 00:41:19.480
(SHEEP BLEATING)

401
00:41:24.860 --> 00:41:26.610
(BELL COLLARS RING)

402
00:41:30.860 --> 00:41:31.950
Hey!

403
00:41:32.370 --> 00:41:34.530
You want your head blown off,
you fancy little fuck?

404
00:41:34.620 --> 00:41:36.910
Don't you ever fucking touch me
with those little rat claws again.

405
00:41:37.040 --> 00:41:39.540
Get the fuck back in formation.

406
00:41:40.920 --> 00:41:44.420
I was just wondering
where you're from, that's...

407
00:41:49.470 --> 00:41:51.890
- Caparzo, is it?
- Hey, drop dead, Corporal.

408
00:41:51.970 --> 00:41:53.100
Got you.

409
00:41:53.220 --> 00:41:55.390
And another thing.
Every time you salute the captain,

410
00:41:55.470 --> 00:41:57.680
you make him a target for the Germans.

411
00:41:57.770 --> 00:41:59.560
So do us a favor. Don't do it.

412
00:41:59.640 --> 00:42:02.600
Especially when I'm standing
next to him, <i>capisci?</i>

413
00:42:03.440 --> 00:42:05.730
Corporal, what's your book about?

414
00:42:05.820 --> 00:42:07.530
- Hey. Watch your rifle.
- Sorry.

415
00:42:07.610 --> 00:42:08.860
Actually, it's about the...

416
00:42:08.940 --> 00:42:10.400
It's supposed to be about
the bonds of brotherhood

417
00:42:10.490 --> 00:42:12.410
that develop between
soldiers during war.

418
00:42:12.490 --> 00:42:14.570
Brotherhood?

419
00:42:14.660 --> 00:42:16.240
What do you know about brotherhood?

420
00:42:16.330 --> 00:42:18.450
Get a load of this guy, Fish.

421
00:42:18.580 --> 00:42:21.540
Why don't you ask
the captain where he's from?

422
00:42:21.620 --> 00:42:26.000
Yeah, ask the captain. He'll tell you
everything you wanna know about him.

423
00:42:26.170 --> 00:42:28.260
You wanna explain
the math of this to me?

424
00:42:28.340 --> 00:42:30.630
I mean, where's the sense
of risking the lives of the eight of us

425
00:42:30.760 --> 00:42:32.300
to save one guy.

426
00:42:32.430 --> 00:42:35.550
Twenty degrees.
Anybody wanna answer that?

427
00:42:35.640 --> 00:42:39.180
Reiben, think about
the poor bastard's mother.

428
00:42:39.270 --> 00:42:41.060
Hey, doc. I got a mother, all right?

429
00:42:41.140 --> 00:42:43.690
I mean, you got a mother.
Sarge has got a mother.

430
00:42:43.770 --> 00:42:47.440
I mean, shit, I bet even
the captain's got a mother.

431
00:42:47.520 --> 00:42:50.360
Well, maybe not the captain,
but the rest of us got mothers.

432
00:42:50.440 --> 00:42:52.860
"Theirs not to reason why
Theirs but to do and die"

433
00:42:52.950 --> 00:42:54.780
(MELLISH VOCALIZING)

434
00:42:55.490 --> 00:42:57.280
What the fuck is that
supposed to mean, Corporal, huh?

435
00:42:57.370 --> 00:42:59.040
We're all supposed to die. Is that it?

436
00:42:59.120 --> 00:43:01.870
Upham's talking about
our duty as soldiers.

437
00:43:01.960 --> 00:43:04.460
- Yes, sir.
- We all have orders we have to follow.

438
00:43:04.540 --> 00:43:07.250
And that supersedes everything,
including your mothers.

439
00:43:07.340 --> 00:43:08.920
Yes, sir. Thank you, sir.

440
00:43:09.000 --> 00:43:11.420
Even if you think
the mission's FUBAR, sir?

441
00:43:11.510 --> 00:43:14.510
Especially if you think
the mission's FUBAR.

442
00:43:14.630 --> 00:43:18.310
- What's FUBAR?
- Oh, it's German. Yeah.

443
00:43:18.890 --> 00:43:20.970
Never heard of that.

444
00:43:21.060 --> 00:43:24.350
Sir, I have an opinion on this matter.

445
00:43:25.150 --> 00:43:28.060
Well, by all means,
share it with the squad.

446
00:43:28.150 --> 00:43:30.360
Well, from my way of thinking, sir,

447
00:43:30.480 --> 00:43:32.820
this entire mission
is a serious mis-allocation

448
00:43:32.900 --> 00:43:35.320
of valuable military resources.

449
00:43:35.410 --> 00:43:37.320
Yeah. Go on.

450
00:43:37.410 --> 00:43:39.870
Well, it seems to me, sir,
that God gave me a special gift,

451
00:43:39.990 --> 00:43:43.250
made me a fine instrument of warfare.

452
00:43:43.330 --> 00:43:46.040
Reiben, pay attention.
Now, this is the way to gripe!

453
00:43:46.170 --> 00:43:47.420
Continue, Jackson.

454
00:43:47.500 --> 00:43:49.380
Well, what I mean by that, sir,

455
00:43:49.500 --> 00:43:52.170
is if you was to put me
and this here sniper rifle anywhere,

456
00:43:52.260 --> 00:43:55.010
up to and including one mile
of Adolf Hitler

457
00:43:55.090 --> 00:43:56.800
with a clear line of sight, sir...

458
00:43:56.890 --> 00:43:59.760
Pack your bags, fellas.
War's over. Amen.

459
00:43:59.850 --> 00:44:02.140
Oh, that's brilliant, bumpkin.

460
00:44:02.220 --> 00:44:05.270
So, Captain, what about you?
I mean, you don't gripe at all?

461
00:44:05.350 --> 00:44:07.770
I don't gripe to you, Reiben.
I'm a captain.

462
00:44:07.850 --> 00:44:10.770
There's a chain of command.
Gripes go up, not down. Always up.

463
00:44:10.860 --> 00:44:12.150
You gripe to me,

464
00:44:12.230 --> 00:44:15.780
I gripe to my superior officers,
so on, so on and so on.

465
00:44:15.860 --> 00:44:17.660
I don't gripe to you.
I don't gripe in front of you.

466
00:44:17.740 --> 00:44:19.740
You should know that as a Ranger.

467
00:44:19.870 --> 00:44:21.700
I'm sorry, sir, but...

468
00:44:21.790 --> 00:44:24.620
Let's say you weren't a captain,
or maybe I was a major.

469
00:44:24.700 --> 00:44:26.500
What would you say then?

470
00:44:26.580 --> 00:44:28.380
Well, in that case,

471
00:44:28.460 --> 00:44:30.540
I'd say this is an
excellent mission, sir,

472
00:44:30.630 --> 00:44:33.760
with an extremely
valuable objective, sir,

473
00:44:33.880 --> 00:44:35.300
worthy of my best efforts, sir.

474
00:44:35.380 --> 00:44:40.890
Moreover, I feel heartfelt sorrow
for the mother of Private James Ryan,

475
00:44:40.970 --> 00:44:44.520
and am willing to lay down my life
and the lives of my men,

476
00:44:44.600 --> 00:44:48.060
especially you, Reiben,
to ease her suffering.

477
00:44:49.560 --> 00:44:51.570
- He's good.
- I love him.

478
00:44:51.820 --> 00:44:53.900
(BOTH MAKE KISSING SOUNDS)

479
00:45:02.240 --> 00:45:03.620
Right.

480
00:45:14.420 --> 00:45:16.260
(DISTANT EXPLOSIONS)

481
00:45:16.340 --> 00:45:18.010
(DISTANT GUNFIRE)

482
00:45:37.440 --> 00:45:39.740
(VILLAGERS SHOUTING IN FRENCH)

483
00:45:45.490 --> 00:45:48.710
- Thunder!
- SOLDIER: Flash!

484
00:45:48.790 --> 00:45:52.040
Upham, over there. Reiben, you four go.

485
00:45:55.500 --> 00:45:58.170
<i>(MAN SPEAKING GERMAN
ON LOUDSPEAKER)</i>

486
00:46:01.510 --> 00:46:03.550
REIBEN: Go, go, go, go, go!

487
00:46:08.890 --> 00:46:11.890
- You guys are a sight for sore eyes.
- Sergeant Hill, our relief showed up.

488
00:46:11.940 --> 00:46:13.730
How many are you?

489
00:46:13.810 --> 00:46:16.440
MILLER: Just eight of us.
We're not your relief. Sorry.

490
00:46:16.520 --> 00:46:18.070
You're not the relief,
what do you mean, sir?

491
00:46:18.150 --> 00:46:19.740
We're here for a Private Ryan.

492
00:46:19.820 --> 00:46:22.360
Who? Ryan? What for?

493
00:46:22.450 --> 00:46:23.570
- Is he here?
- Well, I don't know.

494
00:46:23.660 --> 00:46:25.950
Maybe with a mixed unit
on the other side of town.

495
00:46:26.030 --> 00:46:28.120
It's hard to get to. The Germans
punched a hole in our center

496
00:46:28.200 --> 00:46:30.080
a few hours ago,
they cut us right in two.

497
00:46:30.160 --> 00:46:33.670
- What's his name again?
- Ryan. James Ryan.

498
00:46:33.750 --> 00:46:35.130
He dropped in with 101st.

499
00:46:35.210 --> 00:46:38.170
- Goldman, get me a runner up here.
- Runner!

500
00:46:38.250 --> 00:46:39.920
Come on.

501
00:46:43.890 --> 00:46:46.470
Jonesy, make a hole up there!

502
00:46:48.010 --> 00:46:51.140
We got stopped by some intense
rifle action from the eastward.

503
00:46:51.230 --> 00:46:54.940
The Germans have been
reinforcing two regiments all day.

504
00:46:55.020 --> 00:46:57.230
The streets have been quiet
for about 45 minutes.

505
00:46:57.320 --> 00:46:59.820
Most of the German fire now
is concentrated to the westward.

506
00:46:59.900 --> 00:47:01.110
Who's that on the loudspeaker?

507
00:47:01.190 --> 00:47:03.200
That? That's Dagwood Dusseldorf,

508
00:47:03.280 --> 00:47:05.120
our friendly neighborhood
morale officer.

509
00:47:05.200 --> 00:47:08.200
<i>DUSSELDORF: The Statue of Liberty
is kaput.</i>

510
00:47:08.280 --> 00:47:11.660
- "The Statue of Liberty is kaput."
- DUSSELDORF: <i>...kaput.</i>

511
00:47:11.750 --> 00:47:13.540
That's disconcerting.

512
00:47:16.580 --> 00:47:18.170
HILL: Take the second left...

513
00:47:18.250 --> 00:47:21.550
Your father was circumcised
by my rabbi, you prick!

514
00:47:21.630 --> 00:47:24.720
HILL: Private Ryan, James,
probably mis-dropped with the 101.

515
00:47:24.800 --> 00:47:26.760
- Got that?
- Cover!

516
00:47:26.850 --> 00:47:28.760
(MACHINE GUN FIRING)

517
00:47:34.440 --> 00:47:35.850
Go!

518
00:47:40.190 --> 00:47:42.030
(BULLETS WHIZZING BY)

519
00:47:59.840 --> 00:48:02.050
- You sadistic fucking animals!
- Get down.

520
00:48:02.130 --> 00:48:05.220
They know we're not in direct contact.
They're gonna single out the runners.

521
00:48:05.300 --> 00:48:07.010
Yeah. Why do they
keep shooting him up like that?

522
00:48:07.090 --> 00:48:09.770
Long as his lungs have breath in them,
he still carries the message.

523
00:48:09.800 --> 00:48:11.520
- We'd do the same thing.
- No, we wouldn't!

524
00:48:11.600 --> 00:48:14.560
- Wade! Get them ready to travel.
- Yes, sir.

525
00:48:14.640 --> 00:48:16.520
- HILL: Boyd!
- Come on!

526
00:48:16.600 --> 00:48:19.360
Try again. See if you can let
Captain Hamill know we're coming.

527
00:48:19.440 --> 00:48:22.030
What's the rest of Neuville look like?

528
00:48:22.110 --> 00:48:24.490
Next block's got two-storey buildings,
both sides of the street.

529
00:48:24.570 --> 00:48:25.950
- There's a lot of windows.
- ...copy? Over.

530
00:48:26.030 --> 00:48:28.410
And then there's a wide open square
with pretty good cover on the left.

531
00:48:28.490 --> 00:48:30.740
- Show me.
- Sarge, hold right here.

532
00:48:30.830 --> 00:48:32.240
Yes, sir!

533
00:48:36.660 --> 00:48:39.290
All right. Let's stay out of this
enfilade and use the buildings.

534
00:48:39.380 --> 00:48:40.500
Try a left hook.

535
00:48:40.590 --> 00:48:42.340
Shoot and scoot,
two of yours, two of mine.

536
00:48:42.420 --> 00:48:44.880
Hastings, Goldman, up front!

537
00:48:46.050 --> 00:48:48.840
- Reiben, Caparzo. Fundamentals.
- They're still jamming us.

538
00:48:48.930 --> 00:48:51.550
Short runs. High and low at the corners.

539
00:48:51.640 --> 00:48:54.100
It's gonna be tight.
Be prepared for close contact.

540
00:48:54.180 --> 00:48:56.020
- Go. Upham.
- Yes, sir.

541
00:48:56.100 --> 00:48:58.230
- You stay with Sergeant Horvath.
- Stay right here.

542
00:48:58.310 --> 00:49:01.940
I'll wear him like underwear, Captain!
Stay with me.

543
00:49:10.070 --> 00:49:11.530
All right, past the end
of the block to the left.

544
00:49:11.620 --> 00:49:12.740
Those are the gates to the square.

545
00:49:12.830 --> 00:49:14.120
Good.

546
00:49:22.130 --> 00:49:23.920
Reiben, where's the captain from?

547
00:49:24.000 --> 00:49:26.170
You figure that one out,
you got yourself a nice prize.

548
00:49:26.260 --> 00:49:27.880
300 bucks, last I heard.

549
00:49:27.970 --> 00:49:31.220
Company's got a pool.
5 bucks gets you in.

550
00:49:35.640 --> 00:49:36.980
Easy.

551
00:49:38.560 --> 00:49:42.440
It's around this corner.
Defilade right up to those gates.

552
00:49:43.610 --> 00:49:46.030
Somebody must know where he's from,
what he did for a living.

553
00:49:46.110 --> 00:49:47.940
I've been with him
since Kasserine Pass,

554
00:49:48.030 --> 00:49:49.200
but I don't have a clue.

555
00:49:49.280 --> 00:49:51.070
My ankles are killing me.

556
00:49:51.160 --> 00:49:54.120
I'll need a wheelchair
before this war is over.

557
00:49:54.200 --> 00:49:56.660
Oh, that's it. Oh, my God.

558
00:49:56.740 --> 00:50:00.000
Got ankles like an old woman.
Like an old...

559
00:50:00.080 --> 00:50:01.790
Oh, God.

560
00:50:03.540 --> 00:50:06.710
Reiben, so, you don't even know
where he went to school?

561
00:50:06.800 --> 00:50:08.010
Captain didn't go to school.

562
00:50:08.090 --> 00:50:11.260
They assembled him at OCS
out of spare body parts of dead GIs.

563
00:50:11.340 --> 00:50:12.720
You gotta pay attention to detail.

564
00:50:12.800 --> 00:50:14.720
I know exactly where he's from
and exactly what he did

565
00:50:14.800 --> 00:50:17.060
'cause I pay attention to detail.

566
00:50:17.140 --> 00:50:20.600
Hey, Upham,
careful you don't step in the bullshit.

567
00:50:25.940 --> 00:50:28.320
- Do it.
- Thunder!

568
00:50:28.400 --> 00:50:31.030
Thunder, or we will fire on you!

569
00:50:31.110 --> 00:50:32.910
(SHOUTING IN FRENCH)

570
00:50:40.910 --> 00:50:42.830
Upham, tell them to show themselves.

571
00:50:42.920 --> 00:50:45.920
(SHOUTING IN FRENCH)

572
00:50:51.380 --> 00:50:52.880
(BABY CRYING)

573
00:50:53.090 --> 00:50:55.470
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

574
00:50:55.640 --> 00:50:57.100
Ask them if they know
where the Germans are.

575
00:50:57.180 --> 00:50:59.100
(BOTH SPEAKING FRENCH)

576
00:51:02.810 --> 00:51:05.690
- What's he saying?
- UPHAM: Something about the children.

577
00:51:06.730 --> 00:51:07.770
They want us to take the children.

578
00:51:07.860 --> 00:51:09.230
MILLER: No, no, no.
We can't take the kids.

579
00:51:09.320 --> 00:51:10.990
We can't take the kids. We can't!

580
00:51:11.070 --> 00:51:14.320
We can't take the kids! No!

581
00:51:17.200 --> 00:51:18.370
UPHAM: They think
they'll be safe with us.

582
00:51:18.450 --> 00:51:20.620
MILLER: It's not gonna be
safe when they're with us!

583
00:51:20.700 --> 00:51:24.750
- It's okay. It's okay.
- Are you nuts? Listen to the captain!

584
00:51:24.830 --> 00:51:28.630
- Are you nuts? Listen to the captain!
- They think they'll be safe with us, sir.

585
00:51:28.920 --> 00:51:32.220
MILLER: Caparzo! Put that kid back!

586
00:51:32.670 --> 00:51:33.970
CAPARZO: It's okay.

587
00:51:34.050 --> 00:51:37.300
- Caparzo! Put that little girl back!
- It's okay. It's okay. It's okay.

588
00:51:37.390 --> 00:51:40.430
Caparzo, give that kid back now!

589
00:51:40.520 --> 00:51:44.560
Upham, how do you say, "It's okay"? I
can't. She reminds me of my niece, sir.

590
00:51:44.640 --> 00:51:46.600
Caparzo, get the kid back up there!

591
00:51:46.690 --> 00:51:48.020
Captain, the decent thing to do

592
00:51:48.110 --> 00:51:50.320
is to at least take her down
the road to the next town.

593
00:51:50.400 --> 00:51:53.650
We're not here to do the decent thing!
We're here to follow fucking orders!

594
00:51:53.740 --> 00:51:56.110
Sarge, take this goddamn kid!

595
00:51:56.860 --> 00:51:59.030
Cover! Cover!

596
00:52:08.330 --> 00:52:11.250
REIBEN: God damn it!
Where'd that come from?

597
00:52:13.050 --> 00:52:16.510
He was on the ground
before we heard the shot.

598
00:52:21.260 --> 00:52:23.180
That's where I'd be.

599
00:52:25.060 --> 00:52:26.270
I didn't see it.

600
00:52:26.350 --> 00:52:29.190
Four hundred fifty yards, Captain.
Maybe a shade under.

601
00:52:29.270 --> 00:52:33.280
I wouldn't venture out there, fellas!
This sniper's got talent!

602
00:52:33.360 --> 00:52:34.610
Jacqueline!

603
00:52:34.690 --> 00:52:36.530
(SCREAMING IN FRENCH)

604
00:52:37.990 --> 00:52:41.450
Please don't cry. I'm gonna take you
back to your mama and papa.

605
00:52:41.530 --> 00:52:43.750
Please don't cry. Come on.

606
00:52:47.000 --> 00:52:48.420
MILLER: Carpy.

607
00:52:59.510 --> 00:53:01.850
- CAPARZO: Captain.
- Hold on, Caparzo.

608
00:53:03.260 --> 00:53:05.430
Help me up. I can walk. I can walk.

609
00:53:05.560 --> 00:53:07.690
Caparzo, stay still!

610
00:53:19.110 --> 00:53:21.410
Two clicks, left wind.

611
00:53:25.080 --> 00:53:26.410
Fish!

612
00:53:27.620 --> 00:53:29.580
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

613
00:53:29.710 --> 00:53:31.380
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

614
00:53:34.420 --> 00:53:37.220
Captain, can you see him
from there? How is he?

615
00:53:37.300 --> 00:53:39.260
Wade, you stay put.

616
00:53:39.380 --> 00:53:41.550
Where's he shot, Captain?

617
00:53:43.390 --> 00:53:45.930
- Captain, can you see him from there?
- You stay there!

618
00:53:46.060 --> 00:53:49.690
Damn it, stay down!
What's the matter with you?

619
00:53:49.770 --> 00:53:53.520
Am I gonna take care of you
if you get hit? Huh?

620
00:53:53.610 --> 00:53:56.860
- Fish, come over here.
- Carpy, put your head down.

621
00:53:56.940 --> 00:54:00.110
Why can't you put your head down?

622
00:54:07.790 --> 00:54:10.620
JACKSON: O my God, I trust in thee.

623
00:54:10.750 --> 00:54:12.750
Let me not be ashamed.

624
00:54:13.630 --> 00:54:16.460
Let not my enemies triumph over me.

625
00:54:26.260 --> 00:54:27.930
Copy it.

626
00:54:28.020 --> 00:54:30.350
Copy it and send it for me.

627
00:54:30.440 --> 00:54:32.900
Carpy, you're gonna send it yourself.
Put it down!

628
00:54:32.980 --> 00:54:36.270
- It's got blood!
- I see it. Carpy, I see it.

629
00:54:40.820 --> 00:54:44.950
It's to my dad. It's
got blood on it, Fish.

630
00:55:12.980 --> 00:55:15.520
We got him. Stay down.

631
00:55:16.400 --> 00:55:18.520
(COUPLE SHOUTING IN FRENCH)

632
00:55:24.240 --> 00:55:28.450
- How bad is it?
- Chest, maybe lung shot.

633
00:55:33.250 --> 00:55:35.290
(BOTH SPEAKING FRENCH)

634
00:55:43.880 --> 00:55:46.430
Get that 30 up the street!

635
00:55:51.220 --> 00:55:52.480
MILLER: Detail!

636
00:55:52.560 --> 00:55:54.640
SOLDIER 1: Clear up!
SOLDIER 2: Clear down!

637
00:56:10.280 --> 00:56:13.200
That's why we can't take children.

638
00:56:19.250 --> 00:56:22.840
Sergeant Horvath, do an ammo check.

639
00:56:22.920 --> 00:56:26.590
Upham, canteens. Fill them up.

640
00:56:27.180 --> 00:56:28.970
- Sergeant Hill.
- Yes, sir.

641
00:56:29.050 --> 00:56:33.430
MILLER: Gather your men. We'll form up
at the northwest corner of the square.

642
00:56:33.520 --> 00:56:35.180
- Jackson!
- Sir.

643
00:56:35.270 --> 00:56:40.060
MILLER: Mellish, check the tower,
hustle back here. Right now. Go!

644
00:56:51.910 --> 00:56:53.540
Fuck Ryan.

645
00:57:04.050 --> 00:57:06.470
- Thunder!
- SOLDIER: Flash!

646
00:57:06.550 --> 00:57:08.090
Come on in.

647
00:57:12.890 --> 00:57:15.140
HILL: Hey, guys, we're looking
for Captain Hamill.

648
00:57:15.220 --> 00:57:16.980
Somewhere down there
across the square.

649
00:57:17.060 --> 00:57:18.350
HILL: Across the square.

650
00:57:18.440 --> 00:57:21.020
SOLDIER: Go easy. Watch for snipers.

651
00:57:21.610 --> 00:57:23.360
Sit down.

652
00:57:39.920 --> 00:57:42.500
Jimmy T, go find Captain Hamill,
bring him in here.

653
00:57:42.590 --> 00:57:43.920
What? Up there?

654
00:57:44.000 --> 00:57:46.760
How the hell should I know?
Would you go look, please?

655
00:57:46.840 --> 00:57:48.800
Thank you, you moron.

656
00:57:50.180 --> 00:57:51.760
All right.

657
00:57:51.840 --> 00:57:55.310
You guys just flake
out here for a while.

658
00:57:57.270 --> 00:58:00.730
Let me get this goddamn
hitchhiker out of my boot.

659
00:58:03.770 --> 00:58:05.570
(SHOUTING IN GERMAN)

660
00:58:10.700 --> 00:58:12.530
Drop your weapons!
Drop your weapons!

661
00:58:12.620 --> 00:58:15.830
- Drop them now!
- Drop the fucking weapons!

662
00:58:18.660 --> 00:58:22.710
- I'll shoot you! I'll shoot you!
- Drop! Drop! Drop them!

663
00:58:25.210 --> 00:58:27.510
Now! Put them down!

664
00:58:28.960 --> 00:58:30.760
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

665
00:58:42.650 --> 00:58:44.060
Clear up!

666
00:58:49.360 --> 00:58:53.070
- Shit. Shit!
- HAMILL: Clear up!

667
00:58:54.530 --> 00:58:56.080
Clear down!

668
00:59:08.050 --> 00:59:11.800
- Enough to make you old.
- Let's hope so.

669
00:59:22.770 --> 00:59:24.270
Fred Hamill, Pathfinders, 101st.

670
00:59:24.350 --> 00:59:27.310
John Miller, 2nd Rangers. Thank you.

671
00:59:29.230 --> 00:59:30.860
We're here looking
for a Private James Ryan.

672
00:59:30.940 --> 00:59:33.950
He's part of your outfit.
Any chance at all you policed him up?

673
00:59:34.660 --> 00:59:37.200
HAMILL: How was the road in?
MILLER: Scenic.

674
00:59:37.740 --> 00:59:41.450
- We lost most of our ammo.
- Not to mention one of our men.

675
00:59:41.950 --> 00:59:45.210
Lieutenant, redeploy that bazooka
to the right side of the road.

676
00:59:45.460 --> 00:59:48.250
- Yes, sir!
- And get Ryan up here.

677
00:59:50.590 --> 00:59:53.510
LIEUTENANT: Ryan! Ryan,
front and center!

678
00:59:54.010 --> 00:59:55.300
Ryan!

679
00:59:58.970 --> 01:00:00.970
Here comes our boy.

680
01:00:08.770 --> 01:00:11.480
Told you he was an asshole.

681
01:00:12.820 --> 01:00:15.110
- Sir, Private Ryan reporting as ordered.
- At ease.

682
01:00:15.650 --> 01:00:19.030
Captain Miller, 2nd Rangers.
He wants a word with you.

683
01:00:20.660 --> 01:00:22.160
This way.

684
01:00:23.000 --> 01:00:25.790
All right. Take a knee.

685
01:00:35.340 --> 01:00:38.680
Private, I'm afraid
I have some bad news for you.

686
01:00:46.350 --> 01:00:50.060
Well, there isn't any real
easy way to say this, so...

687
01:00:52.440 --> 01:00:55.690
So I'll just say it.
Your brothers are dead.

688
01:00:57.110 --> 01:01:00.870
We have orders to come get you

689
01:01:01.870 --> 01:01:04.040
because you're going home.

690
01:01:17.970 --> 01:01:20.590
Oh, my God. My brothers are dead.

691
01:01:28.060 --> 01:01:31.690
(CRYING) I was supposed to
take them fishing when we got home.

692
01:01:34.570 --> 01:01:36.240
(RYAN SNIFFLING)

693
01:01:45.410 --> 01:01:48.580
MILLER: I'm so sorry, James.
I can't tell you how much.

694
01:01:49.920 --> 01:01:54.250
- How... How did they die?
- They were killed in action.

695
01:01:56.760 --> 01:01:59.680
That can't be. They're...

696
01:02:00.430 --> 01:02:04.390
That... That can't be.
My brothers are still in grammar school.

697
01:02:07.770 --> 01:02:10.730
- You're James Ryan?
- Yeah.

698
01:02:11.850 --> 01:02:14.610
James Francis Ryan from Iowa?

699
01:02:15.110 --> 01:02:17.650
James Frederick Ryan, Minnesota.

700
01:02:24.580 --> 01:02:26.830
What? Does that mean
my brothers are okay?

701
01:02:26.910 --> 01:02:28.620
Yeah, I'm sure they're fine.

702
01:02:28.700 --> 01:02:30.500
Are you sure they're okay, though?

703
01:02:30.580 --> 01:02:32.000
We're looking
for a different Private Ryan.

704
01:02:32.080 --> 01:02:34.080
This is just a big foul-up.

705
01:02:34.170 --> 01:02:36.050
How do you know?
How can you be sure?

706
01:02:36.130 --> 01:02:40.260
How do you know the foul-up isn't
that his brothers are okay and that...

707
01:02:40.340 --> 01:02:42.510
Lieutenant, I'm sorry for the trouble.

708
01:02:42.590 --> 01:02:46.760
I just wrote them a letter right
before I left. I got to get home.

709
01:02:48.060 --> 01:02:50.020
I got to get home right now.

710
01:02:50.100 --> 01:02:52.600
- I wanna go home.
- SOLDIER: Easy, now.

711
01:02:53.520 --> 01:02:55.060
- So, where in the hell is our Ryan?
- I don't know.

712
01:02:55.150 --> 01:02:57.230
Are you in touch with your CO?

713
01:02:57.320 --> 01:02:59.190
- That figures.
- What unit's your Ryan in?

714
01:02:59.280 --> 01:03:01.490
Baker Company, 506th.

715
01:03:01.570 --> 01:03:03.110
The guy with the broken foot,
he's 506, right?

716
01:03:03.200 --> 01:03:04.870
Yeah. Charlie, I think.

717
01:03:04.950 --> 01:03:06.620
- You think?
- Yeah.

718
01:03:06.700 --> 01:03:09.950
Ryan? Don't know... Man!

719
01:03:10.040 --> 01:03:12.620
- MILLER: Where was your drop zone?
- Just inside of Vierville.

720
01:03:12.710 --> 01:03:15.580
MILLER: Vierville? How the hell did you
end up way up here?

721
01:03:15.670 --> 01:03:18.920
You got me, sir. C-47 took heavy fire.

722
01:03:19.000 --> 01:03:21.760
Pilot went crazy trying to get out
of there, turning every which way.

723
01:03:21.840 --> 01:03:25.800
Took more fire on the drop.
Got messy. I ended up here.

724
01:03:25.890 --> 01:03:27.930
I haven't seen a single guy
from my stick, sir.

725
01:03:28.010 --> 01:03:29.430
God knows where they are.

726
01:03:29.520 --> 01:03:31.230
Anybody from Baker Company
have, like, a big mouth?

727
01:03:31.310 --> 01:03:33.100
Talk about where the drop zone
might've been?

728
01:03:33.190 --> 01:03:36.690
No, sir, but I know Baker Company
had the same rally point as us.

729
01:03:36.770 --> 01:03:38.020
Show me.

730
01:03:39.440 --> 01:03:40.440
My men are beat.

731
01:03:40.530 --> 01:03:42.490
We're gonna hold up here
for about three hours.

732
01:03:42.570 --> 01:03:45.110
We'll pull out after dark.

733
01:03:45.200 --> 01:03:48.120
Got anything left in this town
like a three-star hotel?

734
01:03:48.200 --> 01:03:51.410
Something with clean sheets
and soft pillows and room service?

735
01:03:51.500 --> 01:03:54.960
- How about a nice, comfy church?
- We'll take that.

736
01:03:55.040 --> 01:03:57.880
What have you heard?
How's it all falling together?

737
01:03:57.960 --> 01:03:59.590
Well, we got the beachhead secure.

738
01:03:59.670 --> 01:04:02.300
Problem is Monty's taking
his time moving on Caen.

739
01:04:02.380 --> 01:04:04.630
We can't pull out till he's ready, so...

740
01:04:04.720 --> 01:04:07.340
- That guy's overrated.
- No argument here.

741
01:04:07.430 --> 01:04:10.220
You gotta take Caen,
so you can take Saint-LG.

742
01:04:10.310 --> 01:04:12.220
You got to take Saint-LG
to take Valognes.

743
01:04:12.310 --> 01:04:13.980
Valognes, you got Cherbourg.

744
01:04:14.060 --> 01:04:17.400
- Cherbourg, you got Paris.
- Paris, you get Berlin.

745
01:04:17.860 --> 01:04:20.230
And then that big boat home.

746
01:04:23.570 --> 01:04:25.110
We sure as hell
could use you around here,

747
01:04:25.200 --> 01:04:27.410
but I understand what you're doing.

748
01:04:27.490 --> 01:04:29.120
- You do?
- Yeah.

749
01:04:29.240 --> 01:04:31.830
I got a couple of brothers myself.

750
01:04:32.370 --> 01:04:34.910
- Good luck.
- Thank you.

751
01:04:35.250 --> 01:04:39.250
No, I mean it. Find him. Get him home.

752
01:04:47.680 --> 01:04:49.680
HORVATH: What's with your hand?

753
01:04:51.140 --> 01:04:52.970
I don't know.

754
01:04:54.680 --> 01:04:56.020
It started in Portsmouth

755
01:04:56.100 --> 01:04:57.770
when they brought us
down for embarkation.

756
01:04:57.900 --> 01:04:59.350
It comes and goes.

757
01:04:59.440 --> 01:05:02.360
Well, you may have to get
yourself a new line of work.

758
01:05:02.440 --> 01:05:05.820
This one doesn't seem
to agree with you anymore.

759
01:05:08.280 --> 01:05:09.820
(LAUGHING)

760
01:05:11.120 --> 01:05:12.450
What?

761
01:05:17.080 --> 01:05:18.670
- What?
- Nothing.

762
01:05:19.460 --> 01:05:22.210
What was the name
of that kid at Anzio?

763
01:05:22.290 --> 01:05:24.800
The one that was always walking
around on his hands, you know?

764
01:05:24.920 --> 01:05:28.510
And he was singing that song
about the man on the flying trapeze.

765
01:05:28.590 --> 01:05:30.300
- Vecchio.
- Vecchio.

766
01:05:30.390 --> 01:05:32.050
(BOTH LAUGHING)

767
01:05:36.890 --> 01:05:38.230
Yeah, Vecchio.

768
01:05:38.310 --> 01:05:40.190
He was a goofy kid.

769
01:05:41.980 --> 01:05:44.940
Remember, he used to pee
a "V" on everybody's jacket

770
01:05:45.030 --> 01:05:48.320
for Vecchio, for victory.

771
01:05:52.950 --> 01:05:56.700
MILLER: He was so short.
He was a midget, wasn't he?

772
01:05:56.790 --> 01:05:59.540
"How did you get to be a Ranger?"

773
01:06:00.790 --> 01:06:02.040
HORVATH: He got shot in the foot once,
didn't he,

774
01:06:02.130 --> 01:06:03.130
when he was walking on his hands?

775
01:06:03.210 --> 01:06:06.170
MILLER: Yeah. He could walk
faster on his hands.

776
01:06:07.300 --> 01:06:10.340
He could run faster on his hands than...

777
01:06:13.260 --> 01:06:14.640
Vecchio.

778
01:06:15.760 --> 01:06:17.020
Yeah.

779
01:06:18.680 --> 01:06:20.020
Caparzo.

780
01:06:26.530 --> 01:06:31.450
You see, when you end up
killing one of your men,

781
01:06:32.320 --> 01:06:35.450
you tell yourself it happened

782
01:06:35.530 --> 01:06:41.170
so you could save the lives
of two or three or 10 others.

783
01:06:42.830 --> 01:06:44.880
Maybe 100 others.

784
01:06:49.090 --> 01:06:52.050
Do you know how many men
I've lost under my command?

785
01:06:52.130 --> 01:06:54.390
- How many?
- Ninety-four.

786
01:06:55.760 --> 01:07:01.560
But that means I've saved the lives
of 10 times that many, doesn't it?

787
01:07:02.520 --> 01:07:05.940
Maybe even 20, right?
Twenty times as many?

788
01:07:12.070 --> 01:07:14.410
And that's how simple it is.

789
01:07:15.320 --> 01:07:17.030
That's how you...

790
01:07:18.370 --> 01:07:21.040
That's how you rationalize
making the choice

791
01:07:21.120 --> 01:07:23.620
between the mission and the men.

792
01:07:24.080 --> 01:07:27.170
Except this time, the mission is a man.

793
01:07:30.460 --> 01:07:32.930
This Ryan better be worth it.

794
01:07:35.930 --> 01:07:38.720
He'd better go home,
cure some disease,

795
01:07:38.810 --> 01:07:42.310
or invent a longer-lasting
light bulb or something.

796
01:07:43.100 --> 01:07:44.860
'Cause the truth is
I wouldn't trade 10 Ryans

797
01:07:44.900 --> 01:07:47.690
for one Vecchio or one Caparzo.

798
01:07:47.770 --> 01:07:49.110
Amen.

799
01:07:51.490 --> 01:07:53.610
Look. There it goes again.

800
01:07:54.660 --> 01:07:57.620
Sir, are you all right?

801
01:08:02.870 --> 01:08:06.170
Now, look, we're gonna
move out in two hours.

802
01:08:06.250 --> 01:08:08.540
Why don't you get some sleep?

803
01:08:08.630 --> 01:08:11.670
REIBEN: I don't know how he does it.
MELLISH: What's that?

804
01:08:11.760 --> 01:08:14.420
Falls asleep like that.
I mean, look at him.

805
01:08:14.510 --> 01:08:17.550
The guy's lights out the minute
his head hits the pack.

806
01:08:17.640 --> 01:08:19.220
Clear conscience.

807
01:08:19.300 --> 01:08:20.890
Yeah. What's that saying?

808
01:08:20.970 --> 01:08:24.140
"If God's on our side,
who the hell could be on theirs?"

809
01:08:24.230 --> 01:08:26.810
"If God be for us,
who could be against us?"

810
01:08:26.900 --> 01:08:29.020
REIBEN: Yeah, what did I say?

811
01:08:29.110 --> 01:08:33.360
WADE: Well, actually, the trick to
falling asleep is trying to stay awake.

812
01:08:33.440 --> 01:08:35.240
How is that, Wade?

813
01:08:35.320 --> 01:08:40.280
Well, when my mother was an intern,
she used to work late through the night,

814
01:08:40.370 --> 01:08:42.910
sleep through the day.

815
01:08:43.000 --> 01:08:44.830
So the only time that we ever got
to talk about anything

816
01:08:44.910 --> 01:08:46.370
was when she'd get home.

817
01:08:46.460 --> 01:08:49.000
So what I used to do,
I used to lie in my bed

818
01:08:49.080 --> 01:08:50.590
and try to stay awake
as long as I could,

819
01:08:50.670 --> 01:08:54.420
but it never worked
'cause the harder I tried,

820
01:08:54.510 --> 01:08:56.720
the faster I'd fall asleep.

821
01:08:58.090 --> 01:09:00.100
REIBEN: Yeah. Well, that wouldn't have
mattered none in my house.

822
01:09:00.180 --> 01:09:02.310
My ma, she would've come home,
shook me awake,

823
01:09:02.390 --> 01:09:04.220
chatted me up till dawn.

824
01:09:04.680 --> 01:09:06.850
I swear, that woman
was never too tired to talk.

825
01:09:06.940 --> 01:09:10.940
Yeah. That's probably the only time
she could get a word in.

826
01:09:14.990 --> 01:09:18.530
Funny thing is,
sometimes she'd come home early,

827
01:09:18.610 --> 01:09:21.280
and I'd pretend to be asleep.

828
01:09:21.370 --> 01:09:25.000
- MELLISH: Who? Your mum?
- Yeah.

829
01:09:27.710 --> 01:09:30.710
She'd stand in the doorway,
looking at me.

830
01:09:31.170 --> 01:09:33.590
And I'd just keep my eyes shut.

831
01:09:36.380 --> 01:09:39.970
And I knew she just wanted
to find out about my day,

832
01:09:40.550 --> 01:09:43.010
that she came home early

833
01:09:44.430 --> 01:09:46.390
just to talk to me.

834
01:09:49.600 --> 01:09:53.820
And I still wouldn't move.
I'd still pretend to just be asleep.

835
01:10:01.030 --> 01:10:03.330
I don't know why I did that.

836
01:10:16.880 --> 01:10:20.470
MILLER: We only got a couple of hours.
Shut up and go to sleep.

837
01:10:29.270 --> 01:10:32.100
Captain? Sir?

838
01:10:34.150 --> 01:10:35.610
Corporal?

839
01:10:40.820 --> 01:10:43.910
How you doing there? Are you all right?

840
01:10:44.070 --> 01:10:47.080
Yeah, I think this is
all good for me, sir.

841
01:10:48.500 --> 01:10:49.960
Really?

842
01:10:50.710 --> 01:10:52.210
How is that?

843
01:10:56.130 --> 01:10:58.670
"War educates the senses,"

844
01:10:58.760 --> 01:11:00.720
"calls into action the will,"

845
01:11:00.800 --> 01:11:03.510
"perfects the physical constitution,"

846
01:11:03.890 --> 01:11:06.760
"brings men into such swift
and close collision"

847
01:11:06.850 --> 01:11:09.980
"in critical moments
that man measures man."

848
01:11:10.430 --> 01:11:13.150
Yeah. Well, I guess
that's Emerson's way

849
01:11:13.600 --> 01:11:15.400
of finding the bright side.

850
01:11:15.480 --> 01:11:19.150
- You know Emerson, sir?
- I know some.

851
01:11:23.610 --> 01:11:27.660
So, where are you from, Captain?
What'd you do before the war?

852
01:11:29.660 --> 01:11:32.000
What's the pool up to?

853
01:11:35.330 --> 01:11:38.170
You know, I think it's around 300, sir.

854
01:11:39.000 --> 01:11:41.670
Well, when it gets up to 500,

855
01:11:41.760 --> 01:11:44.010
I'll give you the answers,
and we'll split the money.

856
01:11:44.090 --> 01:11:46.090
How about that?

857
01:11:46.180 --> 01:11:49.760
Well, if that's the way you feel, sir.
I feel it's my duty under your command

858
01:11:49.850 --> 01:11:54.100
to suggest that we wait
until it gets up to 1,000, sir.

859
01:11:55.810 --> 01:11:58.320
What if we don't live that long?

860
01:12:01.490 --> 01:12:04.570
- 500?
- 500 would be good, yeah.

861
01:12:04.650 --> 01:12:06.620
- Yes, sir.
- Yeah.

862
01:12:09.240 --> 01:12:12.000
- Get some sleep, Corporal.
- Yes, sir.

863
01:12:22.340 --> 01:12:24.340
(DISTANT EXPLOSIONS)

864
01:13:18.600 --> 01:13:20.810
SOLDIER 1: Who's got sulfa powder?

865
01:13:23.190 --> 01:13:27.360
Medic! My buddy's bleeding!
He needs a tourniquet!

866
01:13:27.450 --> 01:13:28.950
- Wade.
- Yes, sir?

867
01:13:29.030 --> 01:13:30.990
- See what you can do.
- Yes, sir.

868
01:13:31.070 --> 01:13:34.410
Hold on, fellas. It
won't be much longer.

869
01:13:34.580 --> 01:13:36.450
How we doing here?

870
01:13:37.080 --> 01:13:38.370
All right.

871
01:13:38.460 --> 01:13:41.000
Yeah, doing all right.
Don't worry about it.

872
01:13:41.080 --> 01:13:42.840
Doc's in town.

873
01:13:43.300 --> 01:13:44.380
It's all right. It's all right.

874
01:13:44.460 --> 01:13:45.960
Don't worry, fellas.

875
01:13:46.050 --> 01:13:48.590
The 29th Infantry's breaking through,
they'll be here soon.

876
01:13:48.680 --> 01:13:51.050
SOLDIER 1: Plasma.
Anybody got plasma?

877
01:13:51.140 --> 01:13:54.970
- Captain. Hey, Captain.
- Soldier, you want to fill me in?

878
01:13:55.060 --> 01:13:57.020
Yeah. Lieutenant DeWindt, sir.

879
01:13:57.100 --> 01:14:00.730
99th Troop Carrier Squadron,
carrying in 327th Glider Infantry.

880
01:14:00.810 --> 01:14:02.400
This one was mine, sir.

881
01:14:02.480 --> 01:14:03.900
- I was the pilot.
- Private?

882
01:14:03.980 --> 01:14:05.480
- Twenty-two men dead.
- Private, take care of...

883
01:14:05.570 --> 01:14:08.400
I ended up over there without a scratch.
It took my co-pilot's head right off.

884
01:14:08.490 --> 01:14:10.110
Well, where's the unit?
Who are these people?

885
01:14:10.200 --> 01:14:13.200
Well, the guys we came in with, sir,
they headed off first night.

886
01:14:13.280 --> 01:14:14.580
Haven't seen them since.

887
01:14:14.660 --> 01:14:18.710
Meantime, other guys keep showing up,
one, two, half-dozen at a time.

888
01:14:18.790 --> 01:14:21.580
Then some officer'll come along
and patch together a mixed unit,

889
01:14:21.670 --> 01:14:22.870
head off to make trouble, sir.

890
01:14:22.880 --> 01:14:24.130
SOLDIER 2: Water.
I need a canteen over here.

891
01:14:24.210 --> 01:14:26.210
We're looking for a Private James Ryan.

892
01:14:26.300 --> 01:14:28.550
He's in Baker Company,
the 506 of the 101st.

893
01:14:28.630 --> 01:14:30.970
No, you got me, sir.
A lot of guys come in and out of here.

894
01:14:31.050 --> 01:14:32.510
- Upham.
- Yes, sir.

895
01:14:32.590 --> 01:14:34.430
Check out that squad.
See if Ryan's in it.

896
01:14:34.510 --> 01:14:36.180
Yes, sir.

897
01:14:37.560 --> 01:14:39.020
Reiben.

898
01:14:39.520 --> 01:14:43.560
Smell that leg right there.
Find out if it's south of cheese.

899
01:14:49.190 --> 01:14:50.530
WADE: What?

900
01:14:52.280 --> 01:14:53.490
<i>Juden.</i>

901
01:14:55.410 --> 01:14:57.370
- Juden.
- SOLDIER: Keep moving.

902
01:14:57.450 --> 01:14:59.330
- Keep moving!
- Juden.

903
01:15:00.250 --> 01:15:02.620
<i>I'm Juden, you know?</i>

904
01:15:04.880 --> 01:15:07.460
Yeah, I couldn't pry him out of there,
hard as I tried.

905
01:15:07.550 --> 01:15:09.760
- I'd need a winch.
- Yeah.

906
01:15:13.890 --> 01:15:15.180
HORVATH: Stars.

907
01:15:15.550 --> 01:15:20.100
Yep, Brigadier General Amend,
Deputy Commander, 101st.

908
01:15:20.930 --> 01:15:23.480
Some fucking genius had the great idea

909
01:15:23.560 --> 01:15:25.110
of welding a couple of steel plates

910
01:15:25.190 --> 01:15:28.480
onto our deck to keep
the general safe from ground fire.

911
01:15:28.570 --> 01:15:30.150
Unfortunately,
they forgot to tell me about it

912
01:15:30.240 --> 01:15:32.650
until we were just getting airborne.

913
01:15:32.740 --> 01:15:35.740
Well, that's like trying
to fly a freight train. Okay.

914
01:15:36.370 --> 01:15:39.740
Gross overload.
Trim characteristics all shot to hell.

915
01:15:40.120 --> 01:15:43.120
I nearly broke both my arms
trying to keep her level.

916
01:15:43.210 --> 01:15:45.330
(STAMMERING) And when we released,

917
01:15:45.420 --> 01:15:47.710
you know, I out as hard as I could,

918
01:15:47.790 --> 01:15:51.300
tried to gain some altitude
and still keep her from stalling.

919
01:15:51.380 --> 01:15:55.550
We came down like a fucking meteor.
And this is how we ended up.

920
01:15:57.720 --> 01:16:01.020
And the others, they stopped easy
enough okay though, you know?

921
01:16:01.100 --> 01:16:04.850
We were just... We were just
too damn heavy, you know?

922
01:16:04.940 --> 01:16:06.770
The grass was wet.

923
01:16:07.610 --> 01:16:09.730
Downward slope and all.

924
01:16:10.440 --> 01:16:12.360
Twenty-two guys dead.

925
01:16:15.160 --> 01:16:18.660
- All that for a general?
- One man.

926
01:16:20.950 --> 01:16:24.210
- A lot of that going around.
- FUBAR.

927
01:16:24.790 --> 01:16:26.790
- FUBAR.
- FUBAR.

928
01:16:27.540 --> 01:16:28.960
FUBAR.

929
01:16:29.040 --> 01:16:31.170
You all got that right.

930
01:16:31.670 --> 01:16:33.630
Hey, I looked up "FUBAR"
in the German dictionary.

931
01:16:33.670 --> 01:16:34.790
There's no "FUBAR"in there.

932
01:16:34.800 --> 01:16:36.050
- MILLER: Upham.
- Yes, sir?

933
01:16:36.130 --> 01:16:38.770
There's more paratroops out there.
Find out if one of them is Ryan.

934
01:16:38.800 --> 01:16:40.220
UPHAM: Yes, sir.

935
01:16:40.310 --> 01:16:42.970
Oh, you might want
to check these out, sir.

936
01:16:43.060 --> 01:16:44.600
Dog tags.

937
01:16:44.680 --> 01:16:47.600
More than I really want to count, sir.

938
01:16:48.810 --> 01:16:51.650
I've covered a lot of bodies, sir.

939
01:16:51.820 --> 01:16:53.190
MILLER: Jackson.

940
01:16:53.820 --> 01:16:56.650
- Start going through those.
- Yes, sir.

941
01:16:57.910 --> 01:16:59.490
I'll help.

942
01:17:01.700 --> 01:17:04.250
What do you think, Jackson? Do you
think that little prick's in there?

943
01:17:04.330 --> 01:17:07.330
Well, if he is, I'm gonna find him.
I bet that son of a bitch is here.

944
01:17:07.420 --> 01:17:09.330
I got big money saying
this guy's still alive.

945
01:17:09.420 --> 01:17:11.540
MELLISH: 10 bucks says I nail him first.

946
01:17:11.630 --> 01:17:14.260
- Let's see who we got in here.
- You mugs don't stand a chance.

947
01:17:14.340 --> 01:17:16.220
All right, you think this little
shit bird is in here or what?

948
01:17:16.300 --> 01:17:18.010
Just keep looking.

949
01:17:18.470 --> 01:17:20.640
All right. Gary Ianico.

950
01:17:20.720 --> 01:17:22.510
Ben Rubino. Mike Cessacchio.

951
01:17:22.600 --> 01:17:24.390
I swear.
All the guineas are buying it, huh?

952
01:17:24.470 --> 01:17:26.270
MELLISH: Oh, come on,
not the right name.

953
01:17:26.350 --> 01:17:29.350
Wee Willie Winkie,
that's a buddy of yours.

954
01:17:29.600 --> 01:17:31.980
REIBEN: We gotta find this prick.

955
01:17:36.320 --> 01:17:38.150
Where is this son of a bitch?

956
01:17:38.240 --> 01:17:40.780
Don't mix them up, Jackson, all right?
Keep them in your own fucking pile.

957
01:17:40.870 --> 01:17:43.200
How am I supposed to know
who we got?

958
01:17:43.280 --> 01:17:45.950
Why don't you just shut up,
Reiben? All right.

959
01:17:46.040 --> 01:17:49.540
REIBEN: Everybody be friends.
MELLISH: Cranky there, huh?

960
01:17:50.670 --> 01:17:53.460
- I think I got a winner.
- What you talking about?

961
01:17:53.550 --> 01:17:55.000
Ryan.

962
01:17:55.210 --> 01:17:57.800
- Ryan.
- Take a look at that, Mellish.

963
01:17:58.340 --> 01:17:59.630
You know what?
You're a genius. You really are.

964
