01:36:22.190 --> 01:36:23.860
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

1196
01:36:29.030 --> 01:36:31.620
Sir, he says he's sorry about Wade.

1197
01:36:31.700 --> 01:36:33.750
He says he's sorry about Wade, sir.

1198
01:36:33.830 --> 01:36:35.500
Captain.

1199
01:36:35.620 --> 01:36:37.500
Captain, this isn't right.

1200
01:36:37.580 --> 01:36:41.130
You know this. He's a prisoner.
He surrendered.

1201
01:36:41.840 --> 01:36:43.800
He surrendered, sir!

1202
01:36:54.480 --> 01:36:56.190
Tell him

1203
01:36:58.190 --> 01:37:01.530
to march 1,000 paces in that direction,

1204
01:37:01.650 --> 01:37:02.860
then he can take off the blindfold.

1205
01:37:02.990 --> 01:37:04.030
We'll be gone, and he turns himself in

1206
01:37:04.150 --> 01:37:05.950
to the first Allied patrol
he comes across.

1207
01:37:06.030 --> 01:37:07.030
- Thank you, sir.
- REIBEN: You gotta be kidding me.

1208
01:37:07.160 --> 01:37:09.950
- We're letting him go?
- He's a POW, Reiben.

1209
01:37:10.030 --> 01:37:14.370
Can't take him with us.
Our guys'll pick him up sooner or later.

1210
01:37:25.050 --> 01:37:27.300
Only if he doesn't get picked up
by his own Wehrmacht first,

1211
01:37:27.380 --> 01:37:30.050
then thrown back into circulation.

1212
01:37:32.220 --> 01:37:34.640
Captain, you just let the enemy go.

1213
01:37:34.730 --> 01:37:37.640
- This is such bullshit.
- Y'all got that right.

1214
01:37:37.730 --> 01:37:39.730
Bullshit? Right. This is bullshit?

1215
01:37:39.860 --> 01:37:41.900
- Shooting a prisoner, that'd be okay?
- Upham, shut your mouth.

1216
01:37:42.020 --> 01:37:43.070
It's against the goddamn rules!

1217
01:37:43.190 --> 01:37:47.240
Yeah. The goddamn rules
just walked off with your new friend.

1218
01:37:49.160 --> 01:37:53.410
But I guess that was
the decent thing to do, huh, Captain?

1219
01:38:00.210 --> 01:38:02.540
Get your gear. Let's go.

1220
01:38:05.010 --> 01:38:07.090
You heard him. Gear up.

1221
01:38:08.430 --> 01:38:10.260
The Captain just gave you an order.

1222
01:38:10.340 --> 01:38:14.180
Yeah. Like the one he gave
to take this machine gun.

1223
01:38:14.260 --> 01:38:17.390
- That was a real doozy, wasn't it, Sarge.
- Soldier, you are way out of line.

1224
01:38:17.480 --> 01:38:20.730
Yes, sir. That was one hell of a call,
coming to take this nest,

1225
01:38:20.810 --> 01:38:23.570
but what the hell? We only lost
one of our guys, going for it.

1226
01:38:23.650 --> 01:38:25.980
I swear, I hope Mama Ryan's
real fucking happy,

1227
01:38:26.110 --> 01:38:29.650
knowing that little Jimmy's life is a little
bit more important than two of our guys!

1228
01:38:29.780 --> 01:38:32.740
But then again, we haven't
found him yet, have we? Huh?

1229
01:38:34.790 --> 01:38:36.160
- HORVATH: Here you go.
- Get the hell off me!

1230
01:38:36.290 --> 01:38:38.000
HORVATH: Reiben, get up.

1231
01:38:39.790 --> 01:38:42.920
Gear up. Fall in.

1232
01:38:47.960 --> 01:38:50.180
I'm done with this mission.

1233
01:38:55.140 --> 01:38:56.810
Hey! Hey!

1234
01:38:58.770 --> 01:39:00.810
- UPHAM: Sir.
- Don't walk away from your Captain.

1235
01:39:00.940 --> 01:39:03.190
- Reiben, get back in line.
- No, sir.

1236
01:39:03.310 --> 01:39:04.650
I'll spend the rest
of my life in the stockade

1237
01:39:04.770 --> 01:39:06.070
if I have to, but I'm done with this.

1238
01:39:06.150 --> 01:39:08.440
- I'm not gonna ask you again, soldier.
- Captain!

1239
01:39:08.530 --> 01:39:09.860
All right, now. This is bullshit!

1240
01:39:09.990 --> 01:39:12.450
- Fall in!
- You're gonna shoot me over Ryan?

1241
01:39:12.530 --> 01:39:13.910
No. I'm gonna shoot you
'cause I don't like you.

1242
01:39:13.990 --> 01:39:16.950
- UPHAM: Sir, listen...
- Sir, if he wants to go, just let him go!

1243
01:39:17.040 --> 01:39:20.370
Are you letting this happen?
Captain! You see this?

1244
01:39:20.500 --> 01:39:23.540
- Captain? Sir? Sir, Ryan's dead.
- Bullshit!

1245
01:39:23.670 --> 01:39:26.090
- Sir, we have a situation you might...
- That is bullshit!

1246
01:39:26.170 --> 01:39:28.670
Captain, I have a sixth sense about
these things. I know it in my bones.

1247
01:39:28.800 --> 01:39:31.680
We don't kill that son-of-a-bitch kraut.
Now you're gonna shoot me?

1248
01:39:31.800 --> 01:39:34.280
- He's better than you.
- Then why don't you just do it, Sarge?

1249
01:39:34.340 --> 01:39:36.010
Do it, man. Put one in my leg
and give me that...

1250
01:39:36.100 --> 01:39:38.770
I'm gonna shoot you
in your big goddamn mouth!

1251
01:39:38.850 --> 01:39:40.270
Well, put your money
where your mouth is...

1252
01:39:40.350 --> 01:39:41.770
- You don't know when to shut up.
- Do it!

1253
01:39:41.850 --> 01:39:43.440
- You don't know how to shut up.
- Pull the trigger, already!

1254
01:39:43.520 --> 01:39:44.860
Captain, please!

1255
01:39:44.980 --> 01:39:48.190
- What's the pool on me up to?
- What?

1256
01:39:48.320 --> 01:39:51.030
- You are a coward son of a bitch!
- I'm waiting, Sarge.

1257
01:39:51.110 --> 01:39:54.780
Mike, what's the pool
on me up to right now?

1258
01:39:54.870 --> 01:39:56.660
What's it up to?

1259
01:39:57.280 --> 01:40:01.870
What is it, $300? Is that it? 300?
I'm a schoolteacher.

1260
01:40:06.460 --> 01:40:08.710
I teach English composition

1261
01:40:10.050 --> 01:40:12.220
in this little town called
Addley, Pennsylvania.

1262
01:40:12.300 --> 01:40:14.050
The last 11 years,

1263
01:40:14.890 --> 01:40:17.890
I've been at
Thomas Alva Edison High School.

1264
01:40:19.810 --> 01:40:23.480
I was the coach of the baseball team
in the springtime.

1265
01:40:26.020 --> 01:40:27.690
I'll be doggone.

1266
01:40:28.400 --> 01:40:31.650
MILLER: Back home, when I'd tell people
what I do for a living,

1267
01:40:31.740 --> 01:40:34.650
they'd think, "Well, that figures."

1268
01:40:36.530 --> 01:40:38.740
But over here, it's a...

1269
01:40:40.370 --> 01:40:42.040
A big...

1270
01:40:43.290 --> 01:40:44.960
A big mystery...

1271
01:40:46.000 --> 01:40:48.710
So I guess I've changed some.

1272
01:40:51.420 --> 01:40:54.590
Sometimes I wonder
if I've changed so much

1273
01:40:54.670 --> 01:40:59.220
my wife is even going to recognize me
whenever it is I get back to her.

1274
01:41:00.760 --> 01:41:03.310
And how I'll ever be able to...

1275
01:41:05.850 --> 01:41:08.480
To tell her about days like today.

1276
01:41:11.110 --> 01:41:12.480
Ah! Ryan...

1277
01:41:14.190 --> 01:41:17.360
I don't know anything about Ryan.
I don't care.

1278
01:41:18.030 --> 01:41:21.700
The man means nothing to me,
it's just a name. But if...

1279
01:41:23.540 --> 01:41:26.040
You know, if going to Ramelle

1280
01:41:26.160 --> 01:41:27.710
and finding him, so he can go home,

1281
01:41:27.790 --> 01:41:29.420
if that earns me the right
to get back to my wife

1282
01:41:29.500 --> 01:41:33.800
well, then... Then that's my mission.

1283
01:41:35.840 --> 01:41:37.430
You want to leave?

1284
01:41:37.510 --> 01:41:40.550
You want to go off and fight the war?

1285
01:41:43.430 --> 01:41:44.890
All right.

1286
01:41:46.230 --> 01:41:48.770
All right, I won't stop you.

1287
01:41:48.850 --> 01:41:51.440
I'll even put in the paperwork.

1288
01:41:53.400 --> 01:41:57.780
I just know that every man I kill,
the farther away from home I feel.

1289
01:43:22.990 --> 01:43:24.570
<i>(SINGING SOFTLY) By memories</i>

1290
01:43:25.910 --> 01:43:27.950
<i>Of the days gone by</i>

1291
01:43:29.790 --> 01:43:31.580
<i>In my solitude</i>

1292
01:43:32.500 --> 01:43:34.960
<i>You taunt me</i>

1293
01:43:35.040 --> 01:43:38.590
<i>With memories that never die</i>

1294
01:43:39.800 --> 01:43:42.260
<i>I sit in my chair</i>

1295
01:43:42.340 --> 01:43:44.550
<i>Filled with despair</i>

1296
01:43:44.640 --> 01:43:46.470
<i>There's no one</i>

1297
01:43:46.550 --> 01:43:48.970
<i>Could be so sad</i>

1298
01:43:49.850 --> 01:43:51.890
<i>With gloom everywhere</i>

1299
01:43:51.980 --> 01:43:54.600
<i>I sit and I stare...</i>

1300
01:44:08.490 --> 01:44:10.580
Half-track! Cover!

1301
01:44:12.000 --> 01:44:13.710
(ENGINE RUMBLING)

1302
01:44:26.260 --> 01:44:29.810
Who's doing the shooting?
Who's doing the shooting?

1303
01:44:50.700 --> 01:44:53.100
Get ready to move on their left flank!
Take their left flank!

1304
01:44:53.160 --> 01:44:56.040
MELLISH: Hold on
and make sure they're down!

1305
01:45:17.190 --> 01:45:19.810
SOLDIER: 101st! We're coming out!

1306
01:45:27.240 --> 01:45:30.200
That was a recon element, 2nd SS.

1307
01:45:31.530 --> 01:45:35.120
We've been expecting a probe.
That must have been it.

1308
01:45:37.000 --> 01:45:40.420
Captain Miller,
Charlie Company, 2nd Rangers.

1309
01:45:40.500 --> 01:45:42.590
Corporal Henderson,
Easy Company, 501st.

1310
01:45:42.670 --> 01:45:44.170
Ryan. First of the 506th.

1311
01:45:44.260 --> 01:45:46.630
PFC Toynbe, Third of the 506th.

1312
01:45:46.720 --> 01:45:48.680
James Francis Ryan?

1313
01:45:48.760 --> 01:45:51.260
Yes, sir. How'd you guess that?

1314
01:46:03.020 --> 01:46:05.990
MILLER: Looks like you guys
got hit pretty hard.

1315
01:46:06.070 --> 01:46:09.610
HENDERSON: Yes, sir.
Small unit action.

1316
01:46:12.030 --> 01:46:15.620
They came in,
and beat the hell out of us with 88s.

1317
01:46:21.830 --> 01:46:25.380
Tell you what, sir, if you're our
relief, I'm gonna file a complaint.

1318
01:46:25.460 --> 01:46:27.420
I wouldn't blame you.

1319
01:46:28.170 --> 01:46:29.930
Who's your CO?

1320
01:46:31.510 --> 01:46:34.310
HENDERSON: It would have been
Captain Jennings, sir.

1321
01:46:34.390 --> 01:46:38.850
I'm afraid the best we can muster up
right now is a corporal.

1322
01:46:38.940 --> 01:46:41.480
So, what are you guys all about?

1323
01:46:42.060 --> 01:46:44.570
We're here for him. Ryan.

1324
01:46:45.900 --> 01:46:47.360
Me, sir?

1325
01:46:56.700 --> 01:46:59.080
James Francis Ryan of Iowa?

1326
01:46:59.910 --> 01:47:03.380
Yes, sir.
Payton, Iowa, that's correct, but...

1327
01:47:03.460 --> 01:47:05.460
What is this about?

1328
01:47:07.300 --> 01:47:10.090
Your brothers were killed in combat.

1329
01:47:16.890 --> 01:47:18.520
Which ones?

1330
01:47:21.440 --> 01:47:22.940
All of them.

1331
01:47:32.820 --> 01:47:34.410
On the level?

1332
01:47:35.830 --> 01:47:37.790
Yeah. I'm afraid so.

1333
01:47:40.540 --> 01:47:42.500
You might want to take
some time with this.

1334
01:47:42.580 --> 01:47:45.630
If there's someplace
you want to go and...

1335
01:47:54.640 --> 01:47:57.560
- What's this all about?
- Ryan lost his brothers.

1336
01:47:57.640 --> 01:48:00.020
- Which one?
- All of them.

1337
01:48:04.980 --> 01:48:06.360
You...

1338
01:48:08.980 --> 01:48:12.280
You came all the way
out here to tell me that?

1339
01:48:13.990 --> 01:48:16.160
Well, you're going home.

1340
01:48:17.660 --> 01:48:20.240
Our orders are to bring you back.

1341
01:48:23.540 --> 01:48:25.170
Bring me back?

1342
01:48:27.540 --> 01:48:31.050
Corporal Henderson, I don't mean
to leave you even more shorthanded,

1343
01:48:31.130 --> 01:48:32.470
but orders are orders.

1344
01:48:32.550 --> 01:48:35.390
Any communication about when
you're going to be relieved up here?

1345
01:48:35.510 --> 01:48:36.720
Sir, there's no way to tell. I mean,

1346
01:48:36.840 --> 01:48:38.390
we have no idea
what's happening south of us.

1347
01:48:38.470 --> 01:48:39.810
I have my orders, too, sir.

1348
01:48:39.890 --> 01:48:41.810
They don't include me
abandoning my post.

1349
01:48:41.890 --> 01:48:44.810
I understand that,
but this changes things.

1350
01:48:44.890 --> 01:48:47.230
I don't see that it does, sir.

1351
01:48:48.860 --> 01:48:51.900
The Chief of Staff
for the United States Army says it does.

1352
01:48:51.980 --> 01:48:54.820
Sir, our orders are to hold
this bridge at all cost.

1353
01:48:54.900 --> 01:48:57.410
Now, our planes in the 82nd
have taken out every bridge

1354
01:48:57.530 --> 01:48:59.490
across the Merderet
with the exception of two.

1355
01:48:59.580 --> 01:49:01.160
One at Valognes and this one here.

1356
01:49:01.240 --> 01:49:02.500
We let the Germans take them,

1357
01:49:02.580 --> 01:49:04.160
we're gonna lose our foothold
and have to displace.

1358
01:49:04.250 --> 01:49:07.750
MILLER: Private, your outfit
wants to stay, that's one thing.

1359
01:49:07.830 --> 01:49:08.920
But your party's over here.

1360
01:49:09.000 --> 01:49:11.170
Sir, I can't leave
until at least reinforcements...

1361
01:49:11.250 --> 01:49:13.670
You got three minutes
to gather your gear.

1362
01:49:13.760 --> 01:49:15.840
Sir, what about them?
I mean, there's barely hardly enough...

1363
01:49:15.930 --> 01:49:17.430
REIBEN: Hey, asshole!

1364
01:49:18.180 --> 01:49:22.060
Two of our guys already died
trying to find you, all right?

1365
01:49:27.100 --> 01:49:29.770
- Sir?
- That's right.

1366
01:49:39.660 --> 01:49:44.160
- What were their names?
- Irwin Wade and Adrian Caparzo.

1367
01:49:46.120 --> 01:49:47.670
Wade and...

1368
01:49:49.170 --> 01:49:50.630
Caparzo.

1369
01:50:03.010 --> 01:50:05.430
(WHISPERS) It doesn't make any sense.

1370
01:50:07.520 --> 01:50:11.770
It doesn't make sense, sir.
Why? Why do I deserve to go?

1371
01:50:11.860 --> 01:50:16.030
Why not any of these guys?
They all fought just as hard as me!

1372
01:50:19.660 --> 01:50:22.740
Is that what they're
supposed to tell your mother

1373
01:50:22.830 --> 01:50:26.160
when they send her another
folded American flag?

1374
01:50:33.380 --> 01:50:35.800
Tell her that when you found me,

1375
01:50:35.880 --> 01:50:39.550
I was here and I was
with the only brothers that I have left,

1376
01:50:39.680 --> 01:50:42.890
and that there's no way
I was gonna desert them.

1377
01:50:44.060 --> 01:50:46.220
I think she'll understand that.

1378
01:50:46.350 --> 01:50:49.310
There's no way I'm leaving this bridge.

1379
01:51:32.310 --> 01:51:34.400
What are your orders?

1380
01:51:36.230 --> 01:51:39.570
Sergeant, we have crossed
some strange boundary here.

1381
01:51:40.570 --> 01:51:43.160
The world has taken a turn
for the surreal.

1382
01:51:43.240 --> 01:51:46.080
Clearly, but the question still stands.

1383
01:51:46.740 --> 01:51:49.750
I don't know. What do you think?

1384
01:51:50.790 --> 01:51:53.580
HORVATH: You don't want to know
what I think.

1385
01:51:55.460 --> 01:51:57.130
No, Mike, I do.

1386
01:51:58.840 --> 01:52:02.130
Well, part of me thinks the kid's right.

1387
01:52:02.260 --> 01:52:04.760
What's he done to deserve this?

1388
01:52:04.840 --> 01:52:08.810
He wants to stay here, fine,
let's leave him and go home.

1389
01:52:10.100 --> 01:52:11.350
Yeah.

1390
01:52:11.930 --> 01:52:17.020
But another part of me thinks
what if, by some miracle, we stay

1391
01:52:17.110 --> 01:52:19.780
and actually make it out of here?

1392
01:52:20.650 --> 01:52:24.280
Someday we might look back on this
and decide that

1393
01:52:24.360 --> 01:52:27.780
saving Private Ryan
was the one decent thing

1394
01:52:27.870 --> 01:52:30.790
we were able to pull out of this whole

1395
01:52:30.870 --> 01:52:33.000
God-awful, shitty mess.

1396
01:52:34.670 --> 01:52:37.170
That's what I was thinking, sir.

1397
01:52:38.340 --> 01:52:40.500
Like you said, Captain,

1398
01:52:42.300 --> 01:52:44.010
we do that,

1399
01:52:44.470 --> 01:52:47.300
we all earn the right to go home.

1400
01:52:50.140 --> 01:52:51.680
Oh, brother.

1401
01:52:55.140 --> 01:52:57.480
TRASK: This is everything.

1402
01:52:58.190 --> 01:53:03.820
You got the two 30-caliber machine
guns, 17 grenades, 11 Hawkins mines.

1403
01:53:04.570 --> 01:53:07.910
You got the two bazookas,
but they only got eight rounds left,

1404
01:53:07.990 --> 01:53:10.200
and assorted small arms.

1405
01:53:10.330 --> 01:53:13.790
We had a 60 mortar
but an arty round took it out.

1406
01:53:13.870 --> 01:53:16.540
Might as well be spit wads
if they roll on us with tanks.

1407
01:53:16.670 --> 01:53:19.880
- Which they're sure to do.
- What are you thinking, sir?

1408
01:53:20.000 --> 01:53:24.590
Well, I'm thinking they're going to try
to whip around the flanks.

1409
01:53:29.180 --> 01:53:31.430
Unless we can draw
them up this main road here

1410
01:53:31.510 --> 01:53:32.640
in between these buildings

1411
01:53:32.720 --> 01:53:36.690
where all the rubble makes
a bit of a bottleneck.

1412
01:53:36.770 --> 01:53:38.810
- Disable 'em?
- If we can.

1413
01:53:38.900 --> 01:53:40.480
Make that tank a 60-ton roadblock.

1414
01:53:40.560 --> 01:53:42.400
We do that, we got
a fighting chance at their flanks.

1415
01:53:42.530 --> 01:53:44.900
Yes, sir that's good. Split them up.
Don't let them mass anywhere.

1416
01:53:45.030 --> 01:53:47.950
Hit them hard as we can, one-on-one,
and fall back to the bridge.

1417
01:53:48.030 --> 01:53:50.240
Machine gun on the move down here,
and number two up high somewhere

1418
01:53:50.370 --> 01:53:52.370
to piss a little bad news down
on their heads.

1419
01:53:52.450 --> 01:53:54.700
MILLER: That would be the idea.

1420
01:53:55.250 --> 01:53:56.710
Jackson.

1421
01:53:57.370 --> 01:53:59.630
If we can, I'd like to get you up
in that bell tower.

1422
01:53:59.710 --> 01:54:02.750
- Yes, sir.
- Give you a little company if you need it.

1423
01:54:02.880 --> 01:54:04.880
Yes, sir. Some company couldn't hurt.

1424
01:54:04.960 --> 01:54:09.010
I'd say a .30 with about
1,000 rounds would be okay.

1425
01:54:09.090 --> 01:54:11.140
Parker, job opportunity.

1426
01:54:11.220 --> 01:54:13.220
Yeah. Well, it's not the worst idea
ever, Captain.

1427
01:54:13.310 --> 01:54:14.890
It's just that everything depends
on getting the tank

1428
01:54:14.970 --> 01:54:17.060
down this main road for us
to knock out, right?

1429
01:54:17.230 --> 01:54:20.230
