plan on doing that?

1430
01:54:20.730 --> 01:54:21.730
HORVATH: Reiben's right.

1431
01:54:21.810 --> 01:54:23.650
As our esteemed colleague
from the Airborne pointed out,

1432
01:54:23.730 --> 01:54:26.030
what we got here are
a bunch of spit wads,

1433
01:54:26.110 --> 01:54:29.950
so how do we stop the tank
if we get it to commit?

1434
01:54:30.070 --> 01:54:32.450
Give it a rabbit to chase.

1435
01:54:32.580 --> 01:54:35.700
We could hit the tank in the tracks.

1436
01:54:35.790 --> 01:54:37.910
Yeah, but with what?

1437
01:54:39.580 --> 01:54:43.420
- Well, we could try a sticky bomb.
- RYAN: Sticky bomb, sir?

1438
01:54:44.630 --> 01:54:48.470
- Sir, are you making that up?
- No. It's in the field manual.

1439
01:54:48.590 --> 01:54:50.430
You check it out if you want to.

1440
01:54:50.510 --> 01:54:52.600
RYAN: We seem to be out
of field manuals, sir.

1441
01:54:52.680 --> 01:54:54.600
Perhaps you can enlighten us?

1442
01:54:54.680 --> 01:54:56.140
All right, you have
some demolition, don't you?

1443
01:54:56.270 --> 01:54:58.180
Some TNT or some composition B?

1444
01:54:58.270 --> 01:54:59.980
Yeah, that, sir, is the one thing
we got plenty of.

1445
01:55:00.100 --> 01:55:02.740
I got that bridge wired with enough
composition B to blow it twice.

1446
01:55:02.810 --> 01:55:04.820
All right. You can spare some, then.

1447
01:55:04.940 --> 01:55:08.150
You take a standard-issue GI sock,

1448
01:55:08.280 --> 01:55:11.360
cram it with as much
comp B as it can hold,

1449
01:55:11.450 --> 01:55:13.910
rig up a simple fuse,

1450
01:55:13.990 --> 01:55:16.540
then you coat the whole thing
with axle grease.

1451
01:55:16.620 --> 01:55:21.120
That way, when you throw it, it should
stick. It's a bomb that sticks.

1452
01:55:21.210 --> 01:55:22.830
It's a sticky bomb.

1453
01:55:22.960 --> 01:55:25.360
You come up with a better way
to knock the tracks off a tank,

1454
01:55:25.460 --> 01:55:27.050
I'm all ears.

1455
01:55:27.130 --> 01:55:30.670
This is good.
Now we got to surrender our socks.

1456
01:55:45.150 --> 01:55:46.650
Haul away.

1457
01:56:00.660 --> 01:56:04.580
All right, select the field of fire.
Crossfire with the one in the bell tower.

1458
01:56:04.670 --> 01:56:08.000
All right, I can cover
12 to nine from here.

1459
01:56:11.220 --> 01:56:13.340
- Easy!
- I got her!

1460
01:56:47.710 --> 01:56:49.550
Here are the mines.

1461
01:57:00.470 --> 01:57:02.890
For being the best we can do,

1462
01:57:02.980 --> 01:57:06.980
that forward machine gun
is not in a terrible firing position.

1463
01:57:09.650 --> 01:57:12.150
And this position right here,

1464
01:57:14.240 --> 01:57:15.820
this is the Alamo.

1465
01:57:16.410 --> 01:57:20.080
They push us back this far,
last man alive blows the bridge.

1466
01:57:20.160 --> 01:57:22.200
We only got a 30-second delay
on that fuse,

1467
01:57:22.290 --> 01:57:24.330
so let everyone know that
if you are that last man

1468
01:57:24.410 --> 01:57:28.500
you better hurry your ass off,
or you're not going to be alive long.

1469
01:57:28.580 --> 01:57:32.000
Captain? Where am I during all this?

1470
01:57:32.920 --> 01:57:34.880
Never more than
two feet away from me,

1471
01:57:34.970 --> 01:57:37.180
and that's not negotiable.

1472
01:57:38.300 --> 01:57:40.760
I'll get some ammo. Come on.

1473
01:57:43.770 --> 01:57:45.060
- Hey, Upham.
- Yes.

1474
01:57:45.140 --> 01:57:47.020
- Listen to me, all right?
- Yeah.

1475
01:57:47.100 --> 01:57:48.650
- You're listening?
- Yes.

1476
01:57:48.770 --> 01:57:50.810
All right, we're gonna be displacing

1477
01:57:50.940 --> 01:57:52.520
and falling back like crazy
sons of bitches.

1478
01:57:52.610 --> 01:57:53.690
Right up there.

1479
01:57:53.780 --> 01:57:57.240
So you got to be Johnny on the spot
with the ammo, or we're dead.

1480
01:57:57.320 --> 01:57:59.030
- Right.
- You understand that?

1481
01:57:59.110 --> 01:58:01.410
- Johnny on the spot.
- Yeah.

1482
01:58:01.490 --> 01:58:04.620
- You all right?
- Yeah. Yes.

1483
01:58:04.950 --> 01:58:06.210
You know, when we were
shipping out of England

1484
01:58:06.290 --> 01:58:08.250
the supply sergeant was handing
out cartons of cigarettes,

1485
01:58:08.330 --> 01:58:11.460
and I said "No, thank you,
I don't smoke."

1486
01:58:12.460 --> 01:58:14.050
"I don't smoke."

1487
01:58:15.880 --> 01:58:18.840
- Quite a situation, huh?
- Unbelievable.

1488
01:58:20.180 --> 01:58:25.720
Here. Fucked up beyond
all recognition, right?

1489
01:58:26.180 --> 01:58:28.060
You got that right.

1490
01:58:30.310 --> 01:58:31.690
FUBAR.

1491
01:58:34.020 --> 01:58:35.070
Ouch.

1492
01:58:35.360 --> 01:58:36.990
- Yeah, well...
- FUBAR.

1493
01:58:37.070 --> 01:58:39.570
It's going to be a real show, huh?

1494
01:58:39.660 --> 01:58:41.570
Yeah. Okay.

1495
01:58:47.830 --> 01:58:49.500
Take it easy.

1496
01:58:50.670 --> 01:58:52.130
FUBAR.

1497
01:59:28.950 --> 01:59:29.960
<i>(WOMAN ON RADIO SINGING)</i>

1498
01:59:30.040 --> 01:59:34.420
- RYAN: Who's that singing, sir?
- Edith Piaf.

1499
01:59:36.840 --> 01:59:39.380
RYAN: What's she so upset about?

1500
01:59:40.220 --> 01:59:41.760
Her lover left her,

1501
01:59:41.880 --> 01:59:45.350
but she still sees his face
everywhere she goes.

1502
01:59:46.510 --> 01:59:48.390
That would do it.

1503
02:00:17.710 --> 02:00:20.670
"Even life itself only represents you."

1504
02:00:23.800 --> 02:00:26.390
"Sometimes I dream
that I'm in your arms."

1505
02:00:26.470 --> 02:00:28.890
What was that part?
She sang that before.

1506
02:00:28.970 --> 02:00:31.350
- The chorus. It's the chorus.
- The chorus.

1507
02:00:32.100 --> 02:00:34.730
"And you speak softly in my ear"

1508
02:00:36.610 --> 02:00:39.020
"and you say things"

1509
02:00:39.110 --> 02:00:41.530
"that make my eyes close."

1510
02:00:43.860 --> 02:00:45.950
"And I find that marvelous."

1511
02:00:46.030 --> 02:00:48.660
- Again, Upham...
- Yes.

1512
02:00:49.370 --> 02:00:53.710
...to be honest with you,
I find myself curiously aroused by you.

1513
02:00:53.790 --> 02:00:54.790
(MEN LAUGHING)

1514
02:00:54.870 --> 02:00:58.380
- Marvelous.
- No, it's really a melancholy song.

1515
02:00:58.460 --> 02:01:02.170
At the beginning of the song, she says,
"And then one day, you left."

1516
02:01:02.300 --> 02:01:06.300
"You left me, and I've been
desperate ever since."

1517
02:01:06.390 --> 02:01:09.560
"I see you all over the sky,
I see you all over the Earth."

1518
02:01:09.640 --> 02:01:11.310
Jesus, Upham,
any more songs like this,

1519
02:01:11.390 --> 02:01:13.110
the krauts aren't going
to have to shoot me.

1520
02:01:13.180 --> 02:01:16.020
I'm just going to slit my own wrists.

1521
02:01:16.150 --> 02:01:18.810
You know,
you're a strange bird, Upham.

1522
02:01:18.900 --> 02:01:20.770
Sorry, it's Edith, you know.

1523
02:01:20.860 --> 02:01:22.860
You know what
that song reminds me of?

1524
02:01:22.990 --> 02:01:25.650
It reminds me of Mrs. Rachel Troubowitz
and what she said to me

1525
02:01:25.740 --> 02:01:27.240
the day I left for basic.

1526
02:01:27.320 --> 02:01:29.870
What, "Don't touch me"?

1527
02:01:29.990 --> 02:01:32.540
No. Mrs. Rachel Troubowitz
is our super's wife.

1528
02:01:32.660 --> 02:01:35.460
She comes into my mom's shop
to try on a few things, all right?

1529
02:01:35.540 --> 02:01:39.330
And she's easily, like, a 44 double E.

1530
02:01:39.420 --> 02:01:41.040
- Double E?
- These things are massive.

1531
02:01:41.170 --> 02:01:42.380
Those are big.

1532
02:01:42.500 --> 02:01:45.840
No. And I've got her convinced
that she's, like, a 42 D, all right?

1533
02:01:45.920 --> 02:01:47.630
So we're in the dressing room,
she's trying to squeeze

1534
02:01:47.720 --> 02:01:51.180
into this side-cut,
silk-ribboned, triple-panel girdle

1535
02:01:51.350 --> 02:01:53.520
with the shelf-lift brassiere.

1536
02:01:53.600 --> 02:01:56.190
And it's beautiful 'cause she's just
pouring out of this thing, you know?

1537
02:01:56.270 --> 02:01:58.070
- Is it really tight?
- No, no. It's beautiful.

1538
02:01:58.100 --> 02:01:59.560
And she sees me, and she can tell

1539
02:01:59.690 --> 02:02:02.270
I got a hard-on the size
of the Statue of Liberty, all right?

1540
02:02:02.360 --> 02:02:04.400
And she says to me,
"Richard, calm down."

1541
02:02:04.530 --> 02:02:06.990
And she says, "When you're over there,"

1542
02:02:07.070 --> 02:02:08.950
"if you see anything that upsets you,"

1543
02:02:09.030 --> 02:02:12.120
"or if you're ever scared,
I want you to close your eyes"

1544
02:02:12.200 --> 02:02:15.250
"and think of these. You understand?"

1545
02:02:16.710 --> 02:02:18.870
So I said, "Yes, ma'am."

1546
02:02:32.050 --> 02:02:34.060
RYAN: Are you all right, sir?

1547
02:02:35.100 --> 02:02:37.890
Yeah, I'm just keeping the rhythm.

1548
02:02:42.770 --> 02:02:45.730
Is it true you were
a teacher back home?

1549
02:02:46.780 --> 02:02:48.240
Yes.

1550
02:02:48.320 --> 02:02:50.660
See, that's something I could never do,
you know.

1551
02:02:50.740 --> 02:02:55.240
Not after the way me and my brothers
treated our teachers. No, sir.

1552
02:02:57.580 --> 02:03:00.000
I had 1,000 kids like you.

1553
02:03:06.260 --> 02:03:08.920
I can't see my brothers' faces.

1554
02:03:10.260 --> 02:03:12.970
I've been trying,
and I can't see their faces at all.

1555
02:03:13.100 --> 02:03:15.260
Has that ever happened to you?

1556
02:03:15.350 --> 02:03:17.770
You gotta think of a context.

1557
02:03:19.940 --> 02:03:22.060
What does that mean?

1558
02:03:22.150 --> 02:03:23.690
Well, you don't just think
about their faces.

1559
02:03:23.770 --> 02:03:28.440
You think about something specific,
something you've done together.

1560
02:03:32.160 --> 02:03:35.120
Well, when I think of home,
I think of something specific.

1561
02:03:35.200 --> 02:03:38.290
I think of my hammock in the backyard,

1562
02:03:39.120 --> 02:03:43.460
or my wife pruning the rose bushes
in a pair of my old work gloves.

1563
02:03:47.800 --> 02:03:51.090
This one night, two of my brothers came

1564
02:03:51.170 --> 02:03:54.180
and woke me up in
the middle of the night,

1565
02:03:55.010 --> 02:03:58.060
and they said
they had a surprise for me.

1566
02:03:58.640 --> 02:04:01.770
So they took me to the barn,
up into the loft,

1567
02:04:01.850 --> 02:04:04.810
and there was my oldest brother Dan

1568
02:04:05.980 --> 02:04:09.030
(LAUGHING) with Alice. Alice Jardine.

1569
02:04:11.990 --> 02:04:16.200
I mean, picture a girl who just took
a nosedive from the ugly tree

1570
02:04:16.330 --> 02:04:18.910
and hit every branch coming down.

1571
02:04:20.830 --> 02:04:23.500
And Dan's got her shirt off.

1572
02:04:23.580 --> 02:04:26.380
So he's working on this bra
and he's trying to get it off

1573
02:04:26.500 --> 02:04:29.670
and all of a sudden,
Sean just screams out,

1574
02:04:30.510 --> 02:04:33.880
"Danny, you're a young man!
Don't do it!"

1575
02:04:36.510 --> 02:04:40.020
And so Alice Jardine hears this
and she screams, and she jumps up,

1576
02:04:40.140 --> 02:04:41.770
and she tries to get
running out of the barn,

1577
02:04:41.850 --> 02:04:43.060
but she's still got this shirt
over her head.

1578
02:04:43.190 --> 02:04:47.360
She goes running right into the wall
and knocks herself out.

1579
02:04:47.480 --> 02:04:51.650
So now Dan is just so mad at us,
he starts coming after us,

1580
02:04:51.740 --> 02:04:54.110
but at the same time,
Alice is over there unconscious.

1581
02:04:54.200 --> 02:04:55.700
He's got to wake her up.

1582
02:04:55.820 --> 02:04:59.080
So he grabs her by a leg
and he's dragging her.

1583
02:04:59.200 --> 02:05:02.370
At the same time, he picks up a shovel
and he's going after Sean.

1584
02:05:02.500 --> 02:05:04.620
And Sean said,
"What are you trying to hit me for?"

1585
02:05:04.710 --> 02:05:06.830
"I just did you a favor."

1586
02:05:08.670 --> 02:05:10.550
And so this makes Dan more angry.

1587
02:05:10.670 --> 02:05:13.590
He tries to swing this thing.
He loses the shovel.

1588
02:05:13.720 --> 02:05:16.390
It goes out of his grasp
and hits a kerosene lantern.

1589
02:05:16.510 --> 02:05:19.100
The thing explodes,
the whole barn almost goes up

1590
02:05:19.220 --> 02:05:21.390
because of this thing.

1591
02:05:36.240 --> 02:05:38.120
That was it. That was the last...
That was...

1592
02:05:38.240 --> 02:05:39.780
Dan went off to basic next day.

1593
02:05:39.910 --> 02:05:43.500
That was the last night
the four of us were together.

1594
02:05:43.580 --> 02:05:45.710
That was two years ago.

1595
02:05:47.580 --> 02:05:48.960
Oh, my...

1596
02:05:50.920 --> 02:05:54.460
Tell me about your wife
and those rose bushes.

1597
02:05:55.720 --> 02:05:57.090
No.

1598
02:05:58.260 --> 02:06:00.970
No. That one I save just for me.

